    "explanation": "Troubleshooting: (1) Find LB source IP (varies: some LBs use their management IP, some use VIP, some use each node's IP), (2) From the backend server, check iptables or firewalld rules: iptables -L -n | grep <lb-ip>, (3) Check if LB health check uses different interval/timeout that times out, (4) Verify LB health check HTTP Host header matches server's VirtualHost config, (5) Test manually: curl -v http://<server-ip>/health --interface <lb-ip-if-possible>."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle AWR report shows the SQL statement 'SELECT * FROM transactions WHERE amount > 0' is the top SQL by buffer gets, executing 50,000 times per hour with 0 disk reads. What does this indicate?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The query is poorly written and causing excessive I/O", "feedback": "Incorrect. 0 disk reads means data is in buffer cache — no I/O. But high buffer gets can still cause CPU pressure."},
      {"text": "The query is fully cached in the buffer pool (0 disk reads) but is CPU-intensive due to full table scans in memory returning large result sets, and likely needs an index or result filtering", "feedback": "Correct. High buffer gets with 0 disk reads means full table scan in memory. 50,000 executions/hour indicates it's being called very frequently and consuming CPU cycles and cache."},
      {"text": "The query is running optimally since it has 0 disk reads", "feedback": "Incorrect. 0 disk reads doesn't mean optimal — logical I/O (buffer gets) still consumes CPU and cache resources."},
      {"text": "The AWR data is incorrect as a query cannot have buffer gets without disk reads", "feedback": "Incorrect. AWR correctly distinguishes logical reads (buffer gets from cache) and physical reads (disk I/O)."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "High buffer gets with 0 disk reads = full table scan in cache. Still a problem.",
    "explanation": "High buffer gets impact: (1) CPU consumption for scanning cached blocks, (2) Cache pressure — displacing other data from buffer pool, (3) Latch contention on buffer cache latches. Fix: (1) Add index on amount column if high selectivity, (2) Add WHERE clause to further filter (amount > 1000 instead of >0?), (3) Review calling code — is SELECT * needed or can columns be reduced?, (4) Check if query is called from application loop unnecessarily."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application shows error: 'java.net.SocketTimeoutException: Read timed out' in application logs when calling an external payment gateway. The payment gateway team confirms they process the request successfully. What is the likely issue?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The payment gateway is rejecting the request due to authentication failure", "feedback": "Incorrect. Authentication failure would return an HTTP error response, not cause a socket timeout."},
      {"text": "The HTTP socket read timeout on the application side is shorter than the payment gateway's processing time, causing the application to disconnect before receiving the response", "feedback": "Correct. Gateway processes successfully but application's socket timeout fires before the response arrives. The application disconnects; gateway completes processing without the client."},
      {"text": "The network between application and payment gateway is dropping packets", "feedback": "Incorrect. Packet loss would cause connection timeout or retransmission delays, and gateway wouldn't process requests successfully."},
      {"text": "The payment gateway is throttling requests from the application", "feedback": "Incorrect. Throttling results in HTTP 429 errors or connection refusals, not socket timeouts with successful processing."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Gateway succeeds but client sees timeout — timing is the issue, not connectivity.",
    "explanation": "Solutions: (1) Increase HTTP client socket timeout to exceed gateway's max processing time + buffer, (2) Implement proper async/callback pattern if processing is long-running, (3) Use idempotency keys so duplicate requests (after timeout retry) don't create duplicate transactions, (4) Implement exponential backoff on retries, (5) Discuss SLA with gateway team: what is their guaranteed max processing time? Set timeout = max_processing + 20% buffer."
  },
  {
    "question": "After migrating a banking database from Oracle 11g to 19c, an application reports 'ORA-01403: no data found' for a PL/SQL procedure that worked in 11g. The procedure uses implicit cursor with no EXCEPTION handler. What changed?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Oracle 19c changed the default character set causing data corruption", "feedback": "Incorrect. Character set migration issues cause data display problems, not ORA-01403."},
      {"text": "Oracle 19c has stricter enforcement of implicit cursor behavior or a data migration issue left the table empty/different", "feedback": "Correct. ORA-01403 from implicit cursor (SELECT INTO) means no row returned. Either: (1) Data wasn't migrated, (2) Oracle 19c query optimizer chose different plan returning no rows, (3) Different NLS settings affecting date/string comparisons."},
      {"text": "Oracle 19c deprecated PL/SQL implicit cursors", "feedback": "Incorrect. Implicit cursors are not deprecated in Oracle 19c."},
      {"text": "The procedure's EXECUTE privilege was not granted in Oracle 19c", "feedback": "Incorrect. Missing privilege causes ORA-01031, not ORA-01403."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "ORA-01403 = query returned zero rows. Check if data exists and if query conditions still match.",
    "explanation": "Investigation: (1) Run the SELECT statement manually in 19c to see if rows exist, (2) Compare NLS_DATE_FORMAT, NLS_CHARACTERSET between 11g and 19c — date literal comparisons behave differently, (3) Check if migration scripts completed for all tables, (4) Verify optimizer plan change: DBMS_XPLAN.DISPLAY_CURSOR to see if plan is correct, (5) Add proper exception handling: WHEN NO_DATA_FOUND THEN — handle gracefully."
  },
  {
    "question": "A monitoring alert fires for 'CPU steal time > 20%' on a production Linux VM running a banking application. The VM is on a shared hypervisor. What does high steal time indicate?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The application is poorly optimized and wasting CPU cycles", "feedback": "Incorrect. Steal time is a hypervisor-level metric, not related to application efficiency."},
      {"text": "The hypervisor is allocating physical CPU time to other VMs, causing this VM to wait for CPU resources (noisy neighbor problem)", "feedback": "Correct. Steal time (st in top) represents time the VM wanted CPU but the hypervisor gave it to another VM. High steal = noisy neighbor or overcommitted host."},
      {"text": "The VM's CPU limit is set too low in the hypervisor configuration", "feedback": "Partially correct — CPU limits can cause steal time, but noisy neighbor is the broader and more common explanation."},
      {"text": "The application has too many threads causing CPU contention internally", "feedback": "Incorrect. Internal thread contention shows as high user or sys CPU, not steal time."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Steal time is hypervisor's way of saying 'your VM had to wait for CPU that went to someone else'.",
    "explanation": "Actions: (1) Escalate to infrastructure team: which other VMs share this hypervisor host?, (2) Check if a neighboring VM is having a CPU spike at the same time, (3) Request VM migration to a less-loaded hypervisor host, (4) If persistent: request dedicated CPU cores (CPU pinning) for banking production workloads, (5) Consider bare-metal for latency-sensitive banking applications, (6) Monitor: vmstat (st column) or top (Cpu(s): %st)."
  },
  {
    "question": "A WebLogic cluster has 3 managed servers. Server-1 and Server-2 are running. Server-3 fails to start with error: 'This server is not able to communicate with the Administration Server'. Server-3 is in MSI (Managed Server Independence) mode. What does this mean?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Server-3 cannot start because it needs Admin Server for initial configuration", "feedback": "Incorrect. MSI mode specifically enables servers to start without Admin Server contact."},
      {"text": "Server-3 is running in MSI mode and can start independently but cannot apply configuration changes from Admin Server until connectivity is restored", "feedback": "Correct. MSI allows managed servers to boot using cached config (config.xml copy) without Admin Server. The warning is informational — server will run with last known config."},
      {"text": "Server-3 has a network partition and cannot join the cluster", "feedback": "Incorrect. MSI mode handles this specifically — the server starts independently, not that it fails to start."},
      {"text": "The Admin Server SSL certificate has expired blocking Server-3 authentication", "feedback": "Incorrect. SSL expiry would show specific SSL errors, and MSI mode bypasses Admin Server communication anyway."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "MSI = Managed Server Independence — designed for exactly this scenario.",
    "explanation": "WebLogic MSI mode: Managed servers keep a local copy of config.xml. When Admin Server is unreachable, managed servers start using this cache. Limitations: (1) Cannot deploy new applications, (2) Cannot apply config changes, (3) Cluster membership still works via cluster multicast/unicast. Verify MSI is enabled: MANAGED_SERVER_INDEPENDENCE_ENABLED=true in nodemanager.properties or server startup script. After Admin Server recovers, managed servers will re-sync config automatically."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production PostgreSQL database shows: `SELECT * FROM pg_stat_replication` returns 0 rows. The streaming replication standby server shows 'FATAL: could not connect to the primary server' in its logs. What should be checked first?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Check if the standby database disk is full", "feedback": "Incorrect. Disk full on standby would cause different errors (PANIC: could not write to file)."},
      {"text": "Verify pg_hba.conf on the primary has an entry allowing the replication user from the standby's IP, and that recovery.conf/postgresql.conf has correct primary_conninfo", "feedback": "Correct. Replication connection failures are most commonly caused by pg_hba.conf not allowing replication connections from the standby IP, or incorrect connection string in standby's config."},
      {"text": "Restart both primary and standby servers to re-establish replication", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting without diagnosis may not fix the issue and causes unnecessary disruption."},
      {"text": "Increase max_wal_senders parameter on the primary", "feedback": "Incorrect. max_wal_senders limits concurrent replication connections, but if it's 0 rows, the connection isn't even being established yet."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "FATAL: could not connect = authentication or network issue, not replication process issue.",
    "explanation": "Checklist: (1) Primary pg_hba.conf: host replication replicator <standby-ip>/32 md5, (2) Standby recovery.conf (PG < 12) or postgresql.conf (PG >= 12): primary_conninfo = 'host=<primary> user=replicator password=...', (3) Network: can standby telnet/nc to primary on port 5432?, (4) Check replication user exists: SELECT usename FROM pg_user WHERE userepl=true, (5) Check pg_hba.conf was reloaded: SELECT pg_reload_conf()."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application server generates the following every minute in the log: 'DEBUG: Connection pool health check - 50/50 connections active'. An hour later, new user requests start timing out. What is the root cause?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The application has 50 active users consuming all connections normally", "feedback": "Incorrect. 50/50 connections active doesn't confirm 50 active users — connections could be leaked (borrowed but not returned)."},
      {"text": "All connection pool slots are occupied by leaked connections — connections borrowed from the pool but never returned, causing pool exhaustion", "feedback": "Correct. Connection pool full (50/50) for an extended period while new requests timeout indicates connections are being taken but not returned — a classic connection leak."},
      {"text": "The database server has reached its max_connections limit and is rejecting new pool connections", "feedback": "Incorrect. This would show pool connection errors, but the pool shows 50 connections already established (pool is full, not failing to connect)."},
      {"text": "The pool health check is buggy and reporting wrong counts", "feedback": "Incorrect. The subsequent timeout of new requests confirms the pool is indeed exhausted."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Pool stays at 100% for extended period + new requests timeout = connections not returned.",
    "explanation": "Connection leak detection: (1) Enable pool logging: log connection borrow/return with stack traces, (2) Check for unclosed connections in code: missing try-finally or try-with-resources blocks, (3) Enable removeAbandonedTimeout in pool config to auto-close connections held too long, (4) Use `SHOW PROCESSLIST` (MySQL) or `pg_stat_activity` (PG) to see which queries have been running for hours, (5) Fix code to use try-with-resources: try (Connection conn = pool.getConnection()) { ... }"
  },
  {
    "question": "During an incident, you need to check which ports a specific process (PID 12345) is listening on. Which Linux command is most appropriate?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "`ps aux | grep 12345`", "feedback": "Incorrect. ps shows process info but not network ports."},
      {"text": "`lsof -p 12345 -i` or `ss -lntp | grep 12345`", "feedback": "Correct. lsof -p <pid> -i shows network connections for that PID. ss -lntp shows listening ports with PID info. Both are appropriate."},
      {"text": "`netstat -r`", "feedback": "Incorrect. netstat -r shows the routing table, not process-specific port information."},
      {"text": "`ifconfig -a`", "feedback": "Incorrect. ifconfig shows network interface configuration, not process-port mappings."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Need process-specific port info. Which commands link PIDs to ports?",
    "explanation": "Commands for process-port mapping: (1) `lsof -p 12345 -i` — shows all network FDs for PID, (2) `ss -lntp | grep 12345` — shows listening ports with PID (requires root or same user), (3) `cat /proc/12345/net/tcp` — raw but effective, (4) `netstat -antp | grep 12345` — older but still useful. For real-time monitoring: `ss -s` for summary stats, `ss -tnp state established` for established connections."
  },
  {
    "question": "A bank's SLA states 99.9% uptime per month. During a month (30 days), the banking portal was down for 55 minutes. Was the SLA breached?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Yes, because any downtime exceeding 30 minutes in a month is a breach", "feedback": "Incorrect. SLA breach is calculated against the agreed percentage, not an absolute time threshold."},
      {"text": "No, because 99.9% uptime allows 43.8 minutes of downtime per month, and 55 minutes exceeds this — so yes, SLA IS breached", "feedback": "Correct. 99.9% of 30 days = 43,200 - 43.2 minutes = 43,156.8 minutes uptime. Downtime allowance: 43.2 minutes. 55 minutes > 43.2 minutes = SLA BREACH."},
      {"text": "No, because the SLA only applies to business hours", "feedback": "Incorrect. Standard 99.9% SLA typically applies to 24x7 unless specifically defined as business hours only."},
      {"text": "Cannot determine without knowing the exact time of downtime", "feedback": "Incorrect. For 24x7 SLA, time of day is irrelevant to the calculation."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "99.9% = 0.1% downtime. Calculate 0.1% of 30 days in minutes.",
    "explanation": "SLA calculation: 30 days × 24 hours × 60 minutes = 43,200 total minutes. 99.9% uptime = 0.1% downtime allowed = 43,200 × 0.001 = 43.2 minutes. 55 minutes > 43.2 minutes = SLA BREACHED by 11.8 minutes. Common SLA downtime budgets: 99.9% = 43.8 min/month, 99.95% = 21.9 min/month, 99.99% = 4.38 min/month, 99.999% = 26.3 sec/month."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application team reports that after a database failover, the application can't reconnect even though the new primary is accepting connections. The application uses JDBC with a static connection string pointing to the original primary's IP. What is the architectural fix?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Configure the application to retry connections every 5 seconds after failover", "feedback": "Partially correct — retry helps but doesn't solve the static IP problem. Retrying to a failed server achieves nothing."},
      {"text": "Use Oracle SCAN address or virtual IP (VIP) / database alias that automatically resolves to the current primary after failover, instead of hardcoding primary's IP", "feedback": "Correct. Static IP breaks on failover. Use: Oracle SCAN (RAC), Oracle DB alias in tnsnames, or a virtual IP managed by Pacemaker/keepalived that floats between nodes."},
      {"text": "Increase JDBC connection pool size to absorb the connection failure during failover", "feedback": "Incorrect. More connections to a failed IP still fail — pool size is irrelevant."},
      {"text": "Configure the database to keep the same IP address after failover", "feedback": "Incorrect. In a true failover, the new server typically has a different IP. Pretending otherwise creates architectural debt."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Static IP breaks on failover. What abstraction layer survives server changes?",
    "explanation": "Failover-resilient connection patterns: (1) Oracle RAC SCAN address — single DNS name resolving to active nodes, (2) Oracle Transparent Application Failover (TAF) in tnsnames, (3) Virtual IP (VIP) / floating IP managed by cluster software that moves to new primary, (4) DNS-based failover: TTL=30s, update DNS on failover, (5) Connection string with multiple hosts: jdbc:oracle:thin:@(DESCRIPTION=(FAILOVER=ON)(ADDRESS_LIST=...)). Test failover regularly."
  },
  {
    "question": "AppDynamics shows a memory leak in a Java banking application. Heap usage grows steadily from 2GB to 7GB over 8 hours, then crashes with OutOfMemoryError. Which Java tool is MOST appropriate for initial heap analysis?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "jstat -gcutil to monitor GC activity", "feedback": "Useful for GC analysis but doesn't show object-level heap details for leak diagnosis."},
      {"text": "Generate a heap dump using jmap -dump:format=b,file=heap.hprof <pid> and analyze with Eclipse MAT or VisualVM", "feedback": "Correct. Heap dump captures exact state of all objects in memory. Eclipse MAT can identify the largest retained objects, find leak suspects, and show reference chains — essential for memory leak analysis."},
      {"text": "Run javap to decompile the application bytecode for memory analysis", "feedback": "Incorrect. javap is a bytecode disassembler for code analysis, not memory profiling."},
      {"text": "Increase -Xmx to 16GB to prevent the crash", "feedback": "Incorrect. Increasing heap just delays the OOM — the leak will fill any heap size eventually."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Heap dump captures all object instances at a point in time — the gold standard for leak analysis.",
    "explanation": "Memory leak analysis workflow: (1) Take heap dump near OOM: jmap -dump:format=b,file=heap.hprof <pid>, (2) Or configure: -XX:+HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError -XX:HeapDumpPath=/tmp/, (3) Open in Eclipse MAT: look at Dominator Tree (largest retained objects), (4) Find leak suspects: collections that grow unbounded, caches without eviction, static collections accumulating objects, (5) Check reference chain from leak object to GC root. Common causes: unbounded caches, event listeners not deregistered, thread-local variables."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production banking server has `ulimit -n` set to 1024 for the application user. The application starts failing with 'Too many open files' during peak hours when handling 800 concurrent connections. What is the correct fix?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Restart the application to release file descriptors", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting temporarily releases FDs but they'll fill again during peak. Doesn't fix the limit."},
      {"text": "Increase the open file limit in /etc/security/limits.conf for the application user and restart the application process", "feedback": "Correct. ulimit -n 1024 is too low for an application handling 800+ connections. Each connection uses at least one FD. Need headroom beyond connection count for log files, config files, etc."},
      {"text": "Reduce the number of concurrent connections the application accepts", "feedback": "Incorrect. Reducing capacity is not a fix — the business requirement is 800 concurrent connections."},
      {"text": "Add more application servers to distribute connections below 1024 each", "feedback": "Partially valid architecture decision, but the immediate fix is to increase the limit on the existing server."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "ulimit -n is per-process open file limit. FDs are consumed by sockets, files, pipes.",
    "explanation": "Fix: (1) Edit /etc/security/limits.conf: appuser soft nofile 65536, appuser hard nofile 65536, (2) Verify /etc/pam.d/login includes pam_limits.so, (3) For systemd services: LimitNOFILE=65536 in service unit file, (4) Verify after restart: `cat /proc/<pid>/limits | grep 'open files'`, (5) Rule of thumb: limit should be > (expected_connections × 3) + 1000 (for log files, config, etc.), (6) Check system-wide: /proc/sys/fs/file-max."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle session shows WAIT EVENT = 'enq: TX - row lock contention' for 10 minutes. The blocking session is running an UPDATE on the same table but appears to be in a sleep state. What is the most likely explanation?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The blocking session's UPDATE is running a slow query that hasn't committed yet", "feedback": "Incorrect. If the UPDATE completed and entered sleep state without COMMIT, the transaction is still open."},
      {"text": "The blocking session executed an UPDATE and didn't commit or rollback — the transaction remains open with a lock while the session is idle", "feedback": "Correct. Oracle holds row locks until COMMIT or ROLLBACK. A session that ran UPDATE, then became idle (sleeping) still holds all locks from that transaction."},
      {"text": "The waiting session has higher priority and should preempt the blocking session's lock", "feedback": "Incorrect. Oracle doesn't have lock preemption — sessions wait unless the holder releases the lock."},
      {"text": "The enq: TX wait event indicates a system-level lock, not a row-level lock", "feedback": "Incorrect. enq: TX is specifically a transaction (row-level) lock wait event in Oracle."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Lock holder is sleeping — transaction started but not ended. In Oracle, locks are held for the transaction duration.",
    "explanation": "Diagnosis: SELECT s.sid, s.serial#, s.status, s.last_call_et, t.status txn_status FROM v$session s, v$transaction t WHERE s.saddr = t.ses_addr AND s.sid = <blocking_sid>. Last_call_et shows seconds since last activity. Fix: Contact application/user to commit/rollback, or DBA: ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION 'sid,serial#'. Prevention: Set application-level transaction timeouts, ensure all code paths end with COMMIT/ROLLBACK."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Docker container for a banking microservice starts and immediately shows in `docker ps` as 'Exited (1) 2 seconds ago'. `docker logs <container>` shows an empty output. What is likely happening?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The container image is corrupted and needs to be re-pulled", "feedback": "Incorrect. Corrupted image would fail to start with Docker error messages visible in docker events, not empty logs."},
      {"text": "The application process is failing immediately on startup before writing any logs, possibly due to missing environment variables or configuration files", "feedback": "Correct. Empty logs with immediate exit (code 1) means the process crashes before any log output. Common causes: missing required ENV vars, missing config file, port already in use."},
      {"text": "Docker is misconfigured and not capturing stdout logs", "feedback": "Incorrect. Docker log capture is built-in and doesn't need configuration for basic stdout/stderr."},
      {"text": "The container ran out of memory on startup", "feedback": "Incorrect. OOM would show exit code 137 (SIGKILL), not exit code 1 (general error)."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Exit code 1 + empty logs = crash before any output. The app fails before logging framework initializes.",
    "explanation": "Debugging: (1) docker run -it --entrypoint=/bin/sh <image> — open interactive shell instead of running app, (2) Manually execute the app's start command to see error, (3) Check required ENV vars: docker run -e DEBUG=true --env-file=.env <image>, (4) Verify config files are mounted: docker run -v /host/config:/app/config <image>, (5) Check if required port is already in use on host: ss -tlnp | grep <port>, (6) Add early logging to app startup before other initialization."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application reports intermittent errors: 'JDBC Connection is not available, request timed out after 30000ms'. This happens 3-4 times per day, always lasting 2-3 minutes. The database team says DB is healthy during these periods. What should be investigated?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase the JDBC timeout from 30000ms to 60000ms", "feedback": "Incorrect. Increasing timeout masks the symptom — connections are unavailable because the pool is exhausted, not because they're slow."},
      {"text": "Investigate what causes brief connection pool exhaustion every few hours — likely scheduled jobs, batch processes, or a burst traffic pattern at those specific times", "feedback": "Correct. Intermittent, consistent pool exhaustion at specific intervals points to scheduled processes. The pool empties during the burst, then recovers as connections are returned."},
      {"text": "Switch to a different JDBC driver version", "feedback": "Incorrect. JDBC driver changes don't address connection pool management logic."},
      {"text": "Configure the pool to auto-restart when all connections are used", "feedback": "Incorrect. Auto-restarting the pool drops all active transactions — extremely disruptive."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Intermittent + consistent pattern + brief duration = scheduled trigger. Look for cron jobs or batch.",
    "explanation": "Investigation: (1) Note exact timestamps of the 3-4 occurrences, (2) Check crontab: `crontab -l -u appuser` and `cat /etc/cron.*`, (3) Check application scheduled tasks/quartz jobs, (4) Enable pool logging to see which threads are borrowing connections during the burst, (5) If batch job: optimize it to use fewer connections or use dedicated connection pool separate from OLTP pool, (6) Consider async processing for batch operations to avoid competing with real-time traffic."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Linux server running Oracle DB shows: sar -r shows 2% free physical memory and swap usage is 40%. The DBA wants to know if Oracle's SGA is causing memory pressure. What is the best command to check Oracle memory usage?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Run `free -m` and subtract Oracle's PGA from total", "feedback": "Incorrect. free -m shows total memory but doesn't break down Oracle-specific SGA/PGA. Subtraction won't work without per-process details."},
      {"text": "Use `ipcs -m` to check shared memory segments (Oracle SGA is implemented as shared memory), and cross-reference with Oracle's v$sgainfo view", "feedback": "Correct. Oracle SGA is implemented as shared memory segments. ipcs -m shows shared memory with size and owner. Cross-reference with v$sgainfo for Oracle-specific breakdown."},
      {"text": "Run `vmstat -s` to see detailed memory usage breakdown", "feedback": "Incorrect. vmstat -s shows system-level memory stats but not process-specific SGA breakdown."},
      {"text": "Check Oracle alert log for memory allocation messages", "feedback": "Incorrect. Alert log captures errors but isn't a real-time memory monitoring tool."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Oracle SGA = shared memory (IPC). ipcs -m reveals it.",
    "explanation": "Oracle memory analysis: (1) `ipcs -m` — shows SGA shared memory segments, (2) `ps aux | grep pmon` — find Oracle PID, then `cat /proc/<pid>/status | grep VmRSS` for process memory, (3) In Oracle: SELECT * FROM v$sgainfo — shows SGA components, (4) SELECT name, value FROM v$parameter WHERE name IN ('sga_max_size','pga_aggregate_target'), (5) If swap is in use: Oracle SGA should NOT be swapped out. Disable swapping for Oracle SGA: use LOCK_SGA=TRUE or HugeTLB pages."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Kubernetes cluster shows a node in 'NotReady' state. kubectl describe node shows: 'condition type=Ready status=Unknown'. Pods on the node are showing 'Unknown' status. What is the FIRST action the on-call engineer should take?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Delete all Unknown pods and reschedule them on healthy nodes", "feedback": "Incorrect. Deleting pods on a notready node may not work (control plane can't communicate with kubelet) and doesn't address the root cause."},
      {"text": "SSH into the node and check kubelet service status, system resources, and connectivity to the API server", "feedback": "Correct. NotReady + Unknown condition means API server lost contact with the node's kubelet. SSH to node and diagnose directly."},
      {"text": "Cordon the node and drain all pods before investigating", "feedback": "Incorrect. You can cordon from the control plane, but draining Unknown pods may hang. Investigate the node first."},
      {"text": "Scale up the deployment to add more replicas on healthy nodes as a workaround", "feedback": "Partially valid as a workaround, but diagnosing the NotReady node is the primary action."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Unknown status = control plane lost contact with node. Check the node directly.",
    "explanation": "NotReady node diagnosis: (1) SSH to node, (2) `systemctl status kubelet` — is kubelet running?, (3) `journalctl -u kubelet -f` — check kubelet logs for errors, (4) `ping <api-server-ip>` — network connectivity, (5) Check disk space: `df -h` — /var/lib/kubelet full breaks kubelet, (6) Check memory: `free -m`, (7) `systemctl status docker/containerd` — container runtime, (8) If node is unrecoverable: kubectl delete node <name>, replace with new node."
  },
  {
    "question": "During peak banking hours, Oracle shows a sudden spike in 'library cache: mutex X' waits. This coincides with a new application deployment that introduced multiple applications sharing the same database. What is the likely cause?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The new application deployment increased the database connection count beyond max_sessions", "feedback": "Incorrect. Exceeding max_sessions causes ORA-00018 errors, not library cache mutex waits."},
      {"text": "High volume of hard parses from new or non-shared SQL statements overwhelming the library cache, causing mutex contention", "feedback": "Correct. Library cache mutex X waits indicate high contention during SQL parsing. When multiple applications use non-parameterized SQL (literals instead of bind variables), each unique SQL string requires a hard parse and library cache lock."},
      {"text": "The database redo log is full causing library cache operations to wait", "feedback": "Incorrect. Redo log pressure causes log buffer space or log file sync waits, not library cache mutex."},
      {"text": "The new application is using DDL statements that lock the library cache", "feedback": "Incorrect. DDL causes 'library cache lock' waits, not 'library cache: mutex X'."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Library cache mutex = SQL parsing contention. What causes many hard parses?",
    "explanation": "Root cause: Applications using literals instead of bind variables generate unique SQL for each value (SELECT * FROM accounts WHERE id=1001 vs id=1002 are different SQL statements). Each requires hard parse + library cache write lock. Fix: (1) CURSOR_SHARING=FORCE (quick fix, risk of plan changes), (2) Better: fix application code to use bind variables, (3) Review: SELECT COUNT(*) hard_parses FROM v$sql WHERE executions=1 AND last_active_time > SYSDATE-1/24."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Linux server running a critical banking process shows `dmesg` output containing: 'EXT4-fs error (device sda3): ext4_find_entry:1455: inode #234567: comm java: reading directory lblock 0'. What does this indicate?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The Java application has a directory traversal vulnerability", "feedback": "Incorrect. This is a kernel filesystem error message, not an application vulnerability."},
      {"text": "Filesystem corruption on sda3 — the ext4 filesystem has an error reading a directory inode, indicating potential disk hardware failure or filesystem inconsistency", "feedback": "Correct. EXT4-fs error reading directory lblock indicates filesystem corruption. This can cause application errors (file not found, IO error) and risks data loss."},
      {"text": "The Java process is trying to access a file with insufficient permissions", "feedback": "Incorrect. Permission errors show as 'Permission denied' in application logs, not EXT4 filesystem errors in dmesg."},
      {"text": "The /tmp directory is full causing filesystem errors", "feedback": "Incorrect. /tmp full shows ENOSPC errors, not EXT4 directory inode read errors."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "EXT4-fs error in dmesg = kernel-level filesystem problem. This is serious.",
    "explanation": "Critical steps: (1) Run `smartctl -a /dev/sda` — check disk SMART data for reallocated sectors, (2) `fsck /dev/sda3` — ONLY after unmounting or in read-only mode, NEVER on mounted filesystem, (3) Check if similar errors exist for other files: `dmesg | grep 'EXT4-fs error'`, (4) Immediately: take database/application backup, (5) Plan disk replacement if SMART shows failure, (6) In banking: escalate as major incident — data integrity risk."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Change Advisory Board (CAB) rejects a change request to upgrade a banking middleware component. The reason is 'insufficient rollback plan'. The change is scheduled for the next maintenance window in 7 days. What should the team do?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Proceed with the change anyway since it was already approved by the team lead", "feedback": "Incorrect. CAB rejection means the change is NOT approved. Proceeding is unauthorized and violates change management policy."},
      {"text": "Revise the change request with a detailed rollback procedure, re-submit to CAB, and get approval before the maintenance window", "feedback": "Correct. CAB rejection is a formal process outcome. Revise with adequate rollback plan and resubmit. In ITIL, no change proceeds without proper authorization."},
      {"text": "Escalate to the CIO to override the CAB decision", "feedback": "Incorrect. Escalation to override CAB is appropriate for business-critical emergencies, not for a non-emergency change with 7 days to fix the documentation."},
      {"text": "Submit as an Emergency Change to bypass the CAB review", "feedback": "Incorrect. Emergency Change classification is for urgent production issues, not for circumventing a legitimate CAB rejection on a planned change."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "CAB rejection is formal. Proper response is to fix the identified gap and resubmit.",
    "explanation": "ITIL Change Management: CAB exists to ensure changes are safe, well-planned, and reversible. A rollback plan is mandatory because: (1) If deployment fails, team needs documented steps to restore, (2) Rollback plan proves the team has thought through failure scenarios. Good rollback plan includes: specific steps to revert, time estimate for rollback, success criteria, person responsible for decision to rollback. After adding rollback plan, resubmit CR and get CAB approval before proceeding."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application uses WebLogic JDBC connection pool with 'Test Connections On Reserve' enabled. Despite this, stale connections are being returned to the application causing 'Connection is closed' errors. What is the issue?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The database password was changed and all connections became invalid", "feedback": "Incorrect. Password change would cause authentication errors on new connections, not stale 'Connection is closed' on reserved connections."},
      {"text": "The 'Test SQL' query configured for connection testing is too lightweight and doesn't detect stale connections properly, or the DB is closing connections after test but before the application uses them", "feedback": "Correct. Test on reserve validates the connection is alive at reservation time. If the DB closes the connection in the tiny window between test and application use (race condition), stale connection error occurs. Also: weak test SQL may not catch all stale states."},
      {"text": "WebLogic's test on reserve feature is not thread-safe", "feedback": "Incorrect. WebLogic's JDBC pool is production-grade and thread-safe."},
      {"text": "The network firewall is resetting connections that have been idle in the pool", "feedback": "Correct as a separate but related issue. Firewall RST of idle connections is a very common cause — if connections sit in pool longer than firewall's TCP idle timeout, firewall resets them silently. Test on reserve catches this."}
    ],
    "answer": 3,
    "hint": "Test on reserve catches stale connections AT TEST TIME. What if connection dies between test and use?",
    "explanation": "Common causes of stale connections despite 'Test on Reserve': (1) Firewall idle timeout < pool idle time — firewall sends RST silently, (2) DB wait_timeout (MySQL) or session timeout (Oracle profile) closes idle sessions, (3) Solutions: a) Reduce pool idle time below firewall timeout, b) Enable TCP keepalives, c) Use 'Test Reserved Connections' with a validation interval, d) Implement connection validation in application using isValid() or a lightweight query, e) Check firewall TCP idle timeout: usually 300-900 seconds."
  },
  {
    "question": "In a post-incident review for a P1 banking outage, the root cause is identified as a failed change that was not tested in staging. The incident recurred 3 months after a similar incident. What type of ITIL record should be raised and what should it contain?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Raise another Incident record documenting the repeat occurrence", "feedback": "Incorrect. Incident records are for restoring service, not for preventing recurrence of known patterns."},
      {"text": "Raise a Problem record with a Known Error entry, and raise a Change request to implement mandatory staging testing policy as the permanent fix", "feedback": "Correct. Recurring incidents with identified root cause = Problem Management. Known Error documents the root cause and workaround. Change request implements the permanent fix (mandatory staging validation)."},
      {"text": "Raise a Security Incident since the change bypassed testing controls", "feedback": "Incorrect. Unless there's a security breach, this is a process gap, not a security incident."},
      {"text": "Document it in the service desk knowledge base and close the incident", "feedback": "Incorrect. Knowledge base documentation doesn't drive process improvement. A Problem record with a formal change is required."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Recurring incidents with known root cause = Problem Management + Change for permanent fix.",
    "explanation": "ITIL chain: (1) Problem Record: links to both incidents, documents root cause (missing staging validation), (2) Known Error: documents workaround (manual validation checklist) until permanent fix, (3) Change Request: mandatory staging testing gate — automated CI/CD pipeline with staging environment validation, (4) The change should implement: automated test suite, deployment gate requiring staging success before production approval, (5) Problem is closed when Change is implemented and verified as effective."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Kubernetes horizontal pod autoscaler (HPA) is configured for a banking API with minReplicas=2, maxReplicas=10, and CPU threshold 70%. During peak load, CPU reaches 85% but HPA doesn't scale. What should be checked?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Verify the deployment has resource requests defined — HPA requires CPU requests to calculate utilization percentage", "feedback": "Correct. HPA calculates: actual CPU / requested CPU. If requests are not set, HPA cannot compute utilization percentage and won't scale."},
      {"text": "Manually scale the deployment to trigger HPA initialization", "feedback": "Incorrect. Manual scaling doesn't fix HPA configuration issues."},
      {"text": "Check if maxReplicas needs to be increased beyond 10", "feedback": "Incorrect. HPA should scale to maxReplicas before reaching a limit. The issue is it's not scaling at all."},
      {"text": "Restart the metrics-server to refresh CPU metrics", "feedback": "Partially valid if metrics-server is down, but the first check is resource requests configuration."}
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "hint": "HPA needs resource requests to calculate utilization. No requests = no HPA scaling.",
    "explanation": "HPA diagnosis: (1) kubectl describe hpa <name> — look for 'unable to fetch metrics' or 'missing request for cpu', (2) Check deployment: resources.requests.cpu must be set, (3) kubectl top pods — if this fails, metrics-server is down, (4) If metrics-server down: kubectl -n kube-system get pods | grep metrics-server, (5) HPA calculates: (current_cpu_usage / pod_cpu_request) × 100 = utilization%. Without request defined, denominator is unknown → HPA cannot function."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle Data Guard physical standby shows 'MRP0 process stopped' and the standby is 12 hours behind. The primary database is generating 50GB of redo per hour. The standby DBA finds that redo transport is working (redo is arriving) but apply is stopped. What command restores redo apply?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "ALTER DATABASE SWITCHOVER TO STANDBY;", "feedback": "Incorrect. SWITCHOVER changes the role of the database — completely wrong command for restarting apply."},
      {"text": "ALTER DATABASE RECOVER MANAGED STANDBY DATABASE DISCONNECT FROM SESSION;", "feedback": "Correct. This command starts MRP0 (Managed Recovery Process) to resume redo apply on the standby database."},
      {"text": "STARTUP MOUNT FORCE;", "feedback": "Incorrect. STARTUP FORCE restarts the database instance — disruptive and not needed just to restart apply."},
      {"text": "ALTER SYSTEM SWITCH LOGFILE;", "feedback": "Incorrect. This forces a log switch on the PRIMARY database — irrelevant to standby apply."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "MRP = Managed Recovery Process. What command starts managed recovery?",
    "explanation": "Data Guard apply restart: ALTER DATABASE RECOVER MANAGED STANDBY DATABASE DISCONNECT FROM SESSION. Options: (1) DISCONNECT FROM SESSION — runs in background (recommended), (2) USING CURRENT LOGFILE — apply from current redo (real-time apply), (3) PARALLEL n — use n parallel recovery processes. Monitor: SELECT process, status, sequence#, block# FROM v$managed_standby. After 12 hours of lag at 50GB/hour = 600GB to catch up. Monitor progress: SELECT * FROM v$dataguard_stats."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking team needs to analyze why CPU spiked to 100% on a Linux server at 2 AM last night, but the spike is now over. Which tool provides historical CPU data for post-incident analysis?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "top command with batch mode", "feedback": "Incorrect. top shows real-time data — it cannot show historical data from last night."},
      {"text": "`sar -u` from the sysstat package, which stores historical system performance data", "feedback": "Correct. sar (System Activity Reporter) records CPU, memory, I/O statistics periodically and stores them. `sar -u -f /var/log/sa/sa<date>` retrieves historical data."},
      {"text": "`ps aux` with timestamp filtering", "feedback": "Incorrect. ps shows current process state — not historical snapshots."},
      {"text": "`dmesg | grep cpu` to find CPU events in kernel log", "feedback": "Incorrect. dmesg shows kernel messages not CPU utilization history."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Post-incident analysis needs historical data. sysstat/sar stores it.",
    "explanation": "sar usage for historical analysis: (1) `sar -u -f /var/log/sa/sa21` — CPU history for the 21st of the month, (2) `sar -u -s 01:00:00 -e 03:00:00 -f /var/log/sa/sa21` — CPU between 1 AM and 3 AM, (3) Additional: `sar -r` (memory), `sar -b` (I/O), `sar -q` (run queue/load average), (4) Check sysstat cron: /etc/cron.d/sysstat — default collects every 10 minutes, (5) For process-level history: consider auditd or application-level logging."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking portal shows an increase in HTTP 503 errors from the load balancer. The load balancer logs show: 'No healthy backend servers available'. All three backend servers are running and responding to direct requests. Health check URL is /ping. What should be verified?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Verify the load balancer's health check port and path match the actual application's /ping endpoint port and path", "feedback": "Correct. If LB health check is configured for port 8080 but app runs on 8443, or /ping returns 404 while /health returns 200, the LB marks all backends as down."},
      {"text": "Restart all backend servers to refresh their health check registration", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting servers doesn't fix a misconfigured health check."},
      {"text": "Increase the load balancer's backend connection timeout", "feedback": "Incorrect. Connection timeout affects slow responses; if servers respond to direct requests, timeout isn't the issue."},
      {"text": "Add more backend servers to the load balancer pool", "feedback": "Incorrect. Adding more servers with the same misconfigured health check just gives more 'unhealthy' backends."}
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "hint": "LB says unhealthy, direct access works. The LB health check is checking something different from what you're testing directly.",
    "explanation": "Health check mismatch scenarios: (1) Port mismatch: LB checks port 80, app runs on 8080, (2) Path mismatch: LB checks /ping, endpoint is /health, (3) Expected status code: LB expects 200, endpoint returns 204, (4) SSL mismatch: LB checks HTTP, app requires HTTPS, (5) Host header: app requires specific Host header that LB doesn't send, (6) Test exactly what LB sends: `curl -v -H 'Host: bankportal.com' http://<server>:<lb-check-port><lb-check-path>`"
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application shows the Splunk query: `index=banking_app sourcetype=app_log | stats count by error_code | sort -count`. The top result shows error_code=DB_CONN_TIMEOUT with 15,000 occurrences in the last hour. What does this tell you and what's the next Splunk query to run?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The application has 15,000 database connections — check DB max connections", "feedback": "Incorrect. 15,000 error occurrences ≠ 15,000 simultaneous connections. These are error events over an hour."},
      {"text": "DB_CONN_TIMEOUT is the dominant error — next query should correlate with time to find when errors started and identify affected transactions", "feedback": "Correct. The error stats give volume; next step is temporal analysis and impact assessment: `index=banking_app error_code=DB_CONN_TIMEOUT | timechart count span=1m` to see error timeline."},
      {"text": "Immediately restart the database connection pool to clear timeout errors", "feedback": "Incorrect. Never restart production components based on log counts alone without correlating with other metrics."},
      {"text": "The database is down — escalate immediately", "feedback": "Incorrect. DB connection timeouts don't definitively mean DB is down. The DB could be slow, pool exhausted, or network issue. Need more investigation."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "First query told you WHAT. Next query should tell you WHEN and HOW MANY users are affected.",
    "explanation": "Splunk investigation workflow: (1) `| timechart count span=1m where error_code=DB_CONN_TIMEOUT` — see when errors started (correlate with change events), (2) `| stats dc(user_id) as affected_users by error_code` — unique users impacted, (3) `| transaction user_id | where error_count > 0` — user sessions with errors, (4) Correlate with infrastructure: Did DB response time increase at the same time? Check AppDynamics/Grafana, (5) Check DB connection pool metrics: pool_size, connections_waiting at error time."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application's microservice architecture shows that Service A calls Service B, which calls Service C. When Service C becomes slow (5 second response), the entire request chain backs up and all threads in Service A are eventually exhausted. What design pattern prevents this?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Implement request queuing in Service A to buffer calls during slowness", "feedback": "Incorrect. Queuing adds latency and still exhausts resources — it just delays the failure."},
      {"text": "Implement a Circuit Breaker pattern on Service A's calls to Service B, which stops forwarding requests when Service B/C is slow, failing fast and protecting Service A's thread pool", "feedback": "Correct. Circuit Breaker (Hystrix/Resilience4j) detects failure/slowness in downstream calls and short-circuits — immediately returning fallback response instead of waiting for the slow service, protecting upstream thread pools."},
      {"text": "Deploy more instances of Service A to handle the backed-up threads", "feedback": "Incorrect. More Service A instances will also exhaust threads waiting on slow Service C — you just have more instances failing."},
      {"text": "Reduce Service A's thread pool size to conserve resources", "feedback": "Incorrect. Smaller thread pool means fewer concurrent users before exhaustion — makes the problem worse."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "One slow downstream service should not bring down the entire chain. What pattern handles this?",
    "explanation": "Circuit Breaker states: (1) CLOSED (normal): requests pass through, (2) OPEN (failure detected): requests fail fast, return fallback, (3) HALF-OPEN (testing): limited requests allowed to test if downstream recovered. Configure: failure threshold (50% of last 20 requests), timeout (5s), recovery attempt interval. Also implement: Bulkhead pattern (separate thread pools per downstream service), Timeout pattern, Fallback responses. Libraries: Resilience4j (Java), Hystrix (legacy), Polly (.NET)."
  },
  {
    "question": "An on-call engineer receives an alert: 'Oracle DB CPU at 95% for 10 minutes'. The DBA runs a query and finds one SQL statement consuming 80% of CPU performing a full table scan on a 500-million-row transactions table. The SQL has no WHERE clause. What is the immediate action?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Add an index to the transactions table immediately", "feedback": "Incorrect. Creating an index on a 500M row table takes time and itself consumes significant resources on a already CPU-stressed system."},
      {"text": "Identify the session running the query and kill it after confirming it's not a critical business process, then analyze the SQL for optimization", "feedback": "Correct. Killing the runaway query immediately relieves CPU. Confirm it's not critical (scheduled job? development query on production?), then optimize: add proper WHERE clause, create appropriate index, schedule for off-hours."},
      {"text": "Bounce the entire database to clear all connections", "feedback": "Incorrect. Database bounce is extreme, causes full outage, and is completely unnecessary for a single rogue query."},
      {"text": "Increase Oracle's CPU_COUNT parameter to handle the load", "feedback": "Incorrect. CPU_COUNT limits Oracle's CPU usage — increasing it doesn't generate more CPU resources."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Immediate: stop the bleeding (kill query). Then: fix the root cause (optimize SQL).",
    "explanation": "Steps: (1) SELECT sql_id, sid, serial#, username, sql_text FROM v$session JOIN v$sql USING (sql_id) WHERE status='ACTIVE' ORDER BY cpu_time DESC — identify the session, (2) Confirm with business: is this expected? (Analytics job? Developer running full scan on prod?), (3) ALTER SYSTEM KILL SESSION 'sid,serial#' IMMEDIATE, (4) Post-kill: analyze SQL — add proper WHERE clause, create functional index if needed, (5) Implement: profile/trace the application module sending this SQL, add query timeout at app level."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production Kubernetes cluster shows that a ConfigMap was accidentally deleted. The pods that reference this ConfigMap are now failing with 'configmap not found'. What is the fastest recovery path?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Recreate pods without the ConfigMap reference as a temporary fix", "feedback": "Incorrect. Removing ConfigMap reference from pods would lose all configuration — the application likely cannot function without it."},
      {"text": "Restore the ConfigMap from version control (GitOps) or from a backup, then restart the affected pods", "feedback": "Correct. ConfigMaps should be in version control (GitOps/Helm). Restore from git: `kubectl apply -f configmap.yaml`. Pods referencing environment variables from ConfigMap need restart; mounted volumes auto-update."},
      {"text": "Scale down the deployment to 0 and scale back up after the ConfigMap is restored", "feedback": "Partially correct — scale down/up forces pod recreation which picks up the restored ConfigMap — but the sequence is: restore ConfigMap FIRST, then scale down/up if needed."},
      {"text": "Use kubectl rollout undo to restore the previous deployment state", "feedback": "Incorrect. Rollout undo restores deployment spec, not deleted ConfigMaps."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Infrastructure as Code / GitOps: all K8s manifests should be in source control.",
    "explanation": "Recovery: (1) `git show HEAD:k8s/configmap.yaml | kubectl apply -f -` — restore from git, (2) If no git: reconstruct from memory/documentation, (3) For pods using envFrom: pods need restart to re-read ConfigMap, (4) For pods using volumeMount: Kubernetes automatically syncs ConfigMap volume changes within ~60 seconds, (5) Prevention: (a) RBAC: restrict who can delete ConfigMaps, (b) Use Velero for K8s backup/restore, (c) GitOps with ArgoCD/Flux — desired state always in git."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application team reports that SSL certificates on three servers expire in 30 days. The certificate renewal process requires 5 business days. A new server is being added to the cluster next week. What is the BEST approach?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Renew certificates on existing three servers now, then issue a separate certificate for the new server next week", "feedback": "Incorrect. Issuing separate certificates at different times creates certificate management complexity and different expiry dates."},
      {"text": "Plan certificate renewal to cover all four servers simultaneously, starting now — use SAN certificate listing all server hostnames, aligned renewal reduces management overhead", "feedback": "Correct. Renewing all certificates together with a SAN cert covering all servers simplifies management. Staggering increases risk of missed renewals. Starting now respects the 5-day process time."},
      {"text": "Wait until all four servers are ready, then renew all certificates together", "feedback": "Incorrect. Waiting until the new server is ready (next week) leaves only ~3 weeks before expiry with a 5-day process — too close. Start the renewal process now."},
      {"text": "Implement auto-renewal using Let's Encrypt to eliminate manual certificate management", "feedback": "Partially valid long-term recommendation, but not the immediate answer for banking production where Let's Encrypt might not be approved CA."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Certificate management: minimize fragmentation, maintain lead time, plan ahead.",
    "explanation": "Certificate lifecycle management: (1) Start renewal process now (30 days - 5 day process = 25 days buffer), (2) Include new server's hostname in SAN list, (3) Stagger-free renewal: all servers get new cert at same time → single expiry date to track, (4) Banking certificates: typically from commercial CAs (DigiCert, Entrust) — Let's Encrypt may not meet banking security policy, (5) Implement: certificate expiry monitoring alert at 60 days, 30 days, 14 days, (6) Automate with cert-manager (K8s) or Venafi for enterprise."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Linux process running a banking batch job is stuck and not responding to `kill -15 <pid>` (SIGTERM). What is the state of this process likely to be, and what should be done?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The process is in 'Zombie' state (Z) — use `kill -9` to force kill it", "feedback": "Incorrect. Zombie processes are already dead — they can't be killed with any signal. Their parent must be fixed."},
      {"text": "The process is in 'D' (uninterruptible sleep) state — waiting for I/O that hasn't completed. kill -9 won't work either; the process must complete its I/O or the underlying I/O issue must be resolved", "feedback": "Correct. Uninterruptible sleep (D state) means the process is waiting for a kernel I/O operation. It ignores ALL signals including SIGKILL. Only completing the I/O or fixing the underlying storage/NFS issue resolves it."},
      {"text": "The process is using custom SIGTERM handler that needs to be bypassed with SIGKILL", "feedback": "Incorrect. Custom SIGTERM handlers are application-level. The question says the process is completely unresponsive, suggesting kernel D state."},
      {"text": "The process has elevated privileges preventing kill from working", "feedback": "Incorrect. root can kill any process. Elevated privileges don't prevent signal delivery."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Unresponsive to SIGTERM and SIGKILL = kernel D state. This is an I/O kernel wait.",
    "explanation": "D state (uninterruptible sleep): (1) Check: `ps aux | grep <pid>` — STAT column shows 'D', (2) `cat /proc/<pid>/wchan` — shows what kernel function it's waiting in, (3) Common causes: NFS mount hung (stale NFS server), disk I/O hung (failing disk), network filesystem issues, (4) Solutions: fix NFS server, check disk health (`smartctl`), unmount stuck filesystem, (5) If truly stuck: server reboot may be the only option — schedule as emergency maintenance."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking transaction processing application connects to Oracle RAC. After a planned node failure test, some application sessions show 'ORA-03113: end-of-file on communication channel' and cannot reconnect. TAF (Transparent Application Failover) is configured. Why might TAF fail?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "TAF only works with Oracle 12c and above", "feedback": "Incorrect. TAF has been available since Oracle 8i."},
      {"text": "The application session was in the middle of an uncommitted transaction during failover — TAF can reconnect but cannot replay DML statements, so the session gets an error", "feedback": "Correct. TAF reconnects SELECT queries (SELECT failover) automatically, but DML (INSERT/UPDATE/DELETE) within an open transaction cannot be automatically replayed — application receives error and must handle the transaction retry."},
      {"text": "TAF is incompatible with JDBC Type 4 thin drivers", "feedback": "Incorrect. Oracle JDBC thin driver supports TAF for reconnection."},
      {"text": "The RAC cluster's SCAN listener was not restarted after node failure, breaking TAF", "feedback": "Incorrect. SCAN handles connection routing but TAF reconnection doesn't require SCAN listener restart — surviving nodes' local listeners handle it."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "TAF has two types: SESSION failover (reconnect) and SELECT failover (replay selects). DML is different.",
    "explanation": "TAF behavior: (1) SESSION TAF: reconnects to surviving node automatically, (2) SELECT TAF: replays SELECT queries from the point of failure, (3) DML in open transactions: CANNOT be replayed — application receives ORA-03113 or similar and must handle retry, (4) Application design: implement transaction retry logic, (5) For true transparent DML failover: use Oracle Application Continuity (AC) — replays complete transactions including DML using redo log, (6) Configure: FAILOVER_MODE=(TYPE=SELECT)(METHOD=PRECONNECT)(RETRIES=10)(DELAY=5)."
  },
  {
    "question": "An ITIL Change Management team wants to implement a 'Change Freeze' period during the banking year-end processing from Dec 26 to Jan 5. During this period, an urgent security patch needs to be applied. What ITIL process applies?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Skip the security patch during freeze — security can wait 10 days", "feedback": "Incorrect. Security patches for critical vulnerabilities cannot be indefinitely delayed — this creates compliance and security risk."},
      {"text": "Follow the Emergency Change process — get ECAB (Emergency Change Advisory Board) approval with documented risk assessment for applying the patch during freeze", "feedback": "Correct. Emergency Changes have a streamlined approval process. ECAB can convene rapidly to assess risk vs benefit of breaking freeze for security patch. The freeze doesn't override business-critical emergency needs."},
      {"text": "Apply the patch without approval since security patches are always exempt from change freeze", "feedback": "Incorrect. Even urgent security patches require ECAB approval during freeze — blanket exemptions without review are poor governance."},
      {"text": "Wait for the freeze to end, then apply as standard change", "feedback": "Incorrect. If the security vulnerability is being actively exploited, waiting 10 days is unacceptable."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Change freeze doesn't eliminate Emergency Change process — it makes it more rigorous.",
    "explanation": "Emergency Change during freeze: (1) ECAB convenes: security officer, CAB chair, business owner, (2) Risk assessment: vulnerability severity vs risk of applying patch during sensitive period, (3) Testing requirement: even emergency changes need validation plan (test on non-prod first), (4) Rollback plan: especially critical during year-end processing, (5) Communication: inform all stakeholders, have rollback team on standby, (6) Documentation: all actions logged in real-time, post-implementation review mandatory."
  },
  {
    "question": "A team is reviewing AppDynamics data and sees that the 'Loan Application' Business Transaction (BT) has 0.5% error rate normally. After a deployment, it jumps to 12% error rate. The error is 'NullPointerException in LoanService.calculateEMI()'. What should the team do FIRST?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Debug the NullPointerException by adding logging to LoanService.calculateEMI()", "feedback": "Incorrect. Adding logging requires another deployment. With 12% error rate in production, restore service first."},
      {"text": "Immediately rollback the deployment to restore the 0.5% baseline error rate, then investigate the NPE in a lower environment", "feedback": "Correct. 12% error rate (24x increase) in a banking loan application is significant production impact. Rollback first, fix second — never debug production under active failure."},
      {"text": "Implement a try-catch around calculateEMI() as an emergency patch and redeploy", "feedback": "Incorrect. Catching NPE without fixing the null reference just hides the error — loan calculations may silently produce wrong results, which is worse than an error."},
      {"text": "Increase AppDynamics error threshold to reduce alert noise during investigation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Adjusting alert thresholds to hide production errors is not a fix and violates monitoring integrity."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Production impact at 12% error rate = restore first. The ITIL principle: restore service before root cause analysis.",
    "explanation": "Response priority: (1) Assess impact: how many loan applications are failing? 12% of what volume?, (2) Rollback deployment: kubectl rollout undo / WebLogic redeployment / artifact swap, (3) Confirm error rate returns to baseline in AppDynamics, (4) Capture evidence from production before rollback: stack traces, request context, AppDynamics snapshots, (5) Reproduce in staging: find what loan data triggers the NPE, (6) Fix: identify null object (likely a new field introduced in deployment), add null checks, add unit test for this case."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production Oracle database shows ORA-00600: internal error code with arguments [kghrcsig]. This error appears in the alert log once and the database continues running. What should the DBA do?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Immediately shutdown and restart the database as ORA-00600 always indicates database corruption", "feedback": "Incorrect. ORA-00600 is an internal error but doesn't always require immediate restart. The database is still running normally."},
      {"text": "Collect the trace file generated by ORA-00600, search Oracle Support (MOS) for the specific error code and arguments, and open a service request if needed", "feedback": "Correct. ORA-00600 generates a trace file with detailed context. Oracle Support classifies these — some are cosmetic/known bugs, others are serious. MOS Note for the specific argument ([kghrcsig]) will guide next steps."},
      {"text": "Run DBCC CHECKDB to validate database integrity", "feedback": "Incorrect. DBCC CHECKDB is SQL Server command, not Oracle. Oracle equivalent is DBVERIFY (dbv) or RMAN VALIDATE."},
      {"text": "Ignore it since the database is running fine and ORA-00600 is not critical", "feedback": "Incorrect. Never ignore ORA-00600 in production banking. Even if database recovers, the root cause must be understood and documented."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "ORA-00600 always generates a trace file. That file + Oracle Support is the correct path.",
    "explanation": "ORA-00600 procedure: (1) Locate trace file: SELECT value FROM v$diag_info WHERE name='Diag Trace' — look for ora_<pid>_<instance>.trc, (2) Review trace for SQL being executed, segment involved, (3) Search MOS: https://support.oracle.com — search '[kghrcsig]', (4) Run RMAN: BACKUP VALIDATE CHECK LOGICAL DATABASE to verify data integrity, (5) Collect: SELECT * FROM v$database_block_corruption after VALIDATE, (6) Apply recommended Oracle patch if available, (7) Monitor alert log for recurrence."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application's WebLogic Admin Server went down and cannot be restarted. Managed Servers are running fine in MSI mode. The deployment team needs to deploy an urgent hotfix. What are the options?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Deploy directly to Managed Servers using their individual admin ports (7001) bypassing Admin Server", "feedback": "Incorrect. Managed Servers don't accept deployments via their own admin ports in standard WebLogic setup — Admin Server is the deployment controller."},
      {"text": "In MSI mode, deployments cannot be made until Admin Server is restored — fix Admin Server first, then deploy the hotfix", "feedback": "Correct. WebLogic deployments require Admin Server. MSI mode allows managed servers to run independently but not accept new deployments. Admin Server must be restored before the hotfix can be deployed."},
      {"text": "Copy the hotfix JAR directly to the managed server's deployment directory and restart managed servers", "feedback": "Partially possible as a manual override but not supported/recommended. Creates config inconsistency and may not work for EARs."},
      {"text": "Use WLST offline mode to deploy without Admin Server", "feedback": "Incorrect. WLST offline works for domain config changes, not application deployment to running servers."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "WebLogic deployment architecture: Admin Server is the controller. MSI is for runtime, not deployment.",
    "explanation": "Admin Server recovery priority: (1) Check Admin Server startup failure reason: review AdminServer.log and domain/servers/AdminServer/logs/, (2) Common causes: port conflict, JVM crash, license, stuck lock file (.lok), (3) Remove stale lock: rm $DOMAIN_HOME/servers/AdminServer/*.lok, (4) Verify JVM settings haven't changed, (5) While fixing: communicate ETA to hotfix team, (6) Once Admin Server restored: proceed with deployment via Console or WLST online, (7) Long-term: Admin Server HA using NM + watchdog configuration."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking API gateway log shows: 'TLS 1.0 connection attempt from 192.168.1.50'. The security team mandates TLS 1.2 minimum. The client is a partner bank's legacy system. What is the correct resolution path?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Disable TLS 1.2 enforcement temporarily to accommodate the partner bank", "feedback": "Incorrect. Disabling security controls violates banking security policy and regulatory requirements."},
      {"text": "Engage the partner bank to upgrade their system to TLS 1.2. In the interim, implement IP-based ACL to allow only the partner's IP while logging all TLS 1.0 connections with security team approval", "feedback": "Correct. This balances business continuity (partner bank integration) with security (logging, approval, timeline for fix). Disabling the policy entirely is not acceptable."},
      {"text": "Block all connections from 192.168.1.50 immediately", "feedback": "Incorrect. Blocking a partner bank's integration without business impact assessment and partner notification is disruptive."},
      {"text": "Create a separate API endpoint that allows TLS 1.0 for legacy partners", "feedback": "Incorrect. Creating security-policy exceptions without governance approval and without a remediation timeline is poor security governance."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Security vs business continuity: the answer involves both immediate control AND a remediation timeline.",
    "explanation": "TLS version enforcement approach: (1) Notify partner bank: provide TLS 1.2 migration deadline (typically 30-90 days per regulatory guidance), (2) Document the exception with security team approval, (3) Enable detailed logging for all TLS 1.0 sessions, (4) Implement IP allowlisting as an additional control (only partner's known IPs), (5) Test partner's system post-upgrade in UAT before production, (6) Regulatory note: PCI-DSS 3.2+ mandates TLS 1.2 minimum — non-compliance has consequences."
  },
  {
    "question": "A developer accidentally runs `DROP TABLE transactions;` on the production Oracle database. The table contains 10 million critical banking records. Point-in-time recovery is needed. What Oracle feature enables this?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Oracle Flashback Table — undrop the table using the recycle bin", "feedback": "Correct as the FASTEST option. Oracle Flashback Table / UNDROP: FLASHBACK TABLE transactions TO BEFORE DROP — restores table from Oracle recycle bin if it wasn't PURGED."},
      {"text": "Restore from last night's RMAN backup and apply archive logs to current time", "feedback": "Correct but slower. RMAN restore is the fallback if recycle bin is empty (PURGE was used or recycle bin is disabled)."},
      {"text": "Use Oracle LogMiner to reconstruct the table from redo logs", "feedback": "Partially possible — LogMiner can extract DML, but reconstructing 10M rows from redo is extremely slow and complex."},
      {"text": "The data is permanently lost as DROP TABLE is a DDL operation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Oracle recycle bin and RMAN backups enable recovery from DROP TABLE."}
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "hint": "Oracle recycle bin is the fastest path for DROP TABLE recovery. UNDROP.",
    "explanation": "Fastest path: (1) Check recycle bin: SELECT object_name, original_name, type FROM dba_recyclebin WHERE original_name='TRANSACTIONS', (2) If found: FLASHBACK TABLE transactions TO BEFORE DROP, (3) If recycle bin empty (DROP TABLE... PURGE or PURGE RECYCLEBIN was run): restore from RMAN backup, (4) RMAN restore: RECOVER TABLE scott.transactions UNTIL TIME 'SYSDATE-1/24' AUXILIARY DESTINATION '/tmp/aux' REMAP TABLE scott.transactions:transactions_recovered. Prevention: enable recycle bin, daily RMAN backups, restrict DROP TABLE privilege."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking microservice has a memory limit of 512Mi in Kubernetes. After a recent spike in traffic, the pod was OOMKilled. The team wants to add a JVM. What JVM flag is critical when running Java in a container?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "-Xmx512m to limit heap to the container's memory limit", "feedback": "Partially correct, but doesn't fully address the containerization issue."},
      {"text": "Use -XX:+UseContainerSupport (Java 10+) or set -Xmx and -Xms explicitly — without container support, JVM reads host's total RAM instead of container limit", "feedback": "Correct. Pre-Java 10, JVM reads /proc/meminfo (host RAM) to set default heap (25% of total). In a container with 512Mi limit, this causes OOM because JVM allocates heap based on host's 64GB RAM."},
      {"text": "-XX:+UseG1GC to enable G1 garbage collector for better memory management", "feedback": "Incorrect. While G1GC is often better for containers, the critical issue is JVM not respecting container memory limits."},
      {"text": "-XX:MaxRAMPercentage=50 to limit JVM to half the system RAM", "feedback": "Incorrect alone — MaxRAMPercentage without container support still reads host RAM as the base."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "JVM in containers: old JVMs don't know they're in containers and see host RAM.",
    "explanation": "Java container awareness: (1) Java 8u191+/Java 10+: -XX:+UseContainerSupport enabled by default, (2) JVM then reads /sys/fs/cgroup/memory/memory.limit_in_bytes for container limit, (3) Best practice for 512Mi container: -XX:InitialRAMPercentage=50 -XX:MaxRAMPercentage=75 → Xmx ≈ 384Mi, leaving headroom for metaspace, thread stacks, native memory, (4) Verify: `docker run <image> java -XX:+PrintFlagsFinal | grep -i heap`, (5) Total JVM memory = heap + metaspace + thread stacks + native. All count against container limit."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application shows that a PostgreSQL query runs in 50ms in development but takes 8 seconds in production on the same data. EXPLAIN ANALYZE in production shows 'Seq Scan' where development shows 'Index Scan'. What is the most likely cause?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "PostgreSQL version difference between dev and production", "feedback": "Possible but less likely than data-related causes. Versions rarely cause plan changes on identical data."},
      {"text": "Production table statistics are stale causing the query planner to choose a sequential scan instead of the index, because it underestimates/overestimates row counts", "feedback": "Correct. PostgreSQL's query planner uses table statistics (pg_statistic) to choose plans. If statistics are stale (table grew significantly, ANALYZE not run recently), planner may miscalculate selectivity and choose seq scan."},
      {"text": "The index on the production table was dropped and not recreated", "feedback": "Incorrect. If index was dropped, EXPLAIN would show no index exists, and DBA would notice the missing index."},
      {"text": "Production server has insufficient RAM causing index to not fit in memory", "feedback": "Incorrect. Index size vs RAM affects index scan performance but doesn't cause the planner to choose seq scan vs index scan."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Planner chooses seq scan when it thinks it's cheaper based on statistics. Stale stats = wrong choice.",
    "explanation": "Fix: (1) ANALYZE transactions; — update statistics, (2) EXPLAIN ANALYZE — re-run to see if plan changes, (3) Check statistics age: SELECT last_analyze, last_autoanalyze FROM pg_stat_user_tables WHERE relname='transactions', (4) Tune autovacuum for large frequently-updated tables: autovacuum_analyze_scale_factor = 0.01 (analyze after 1% change instead of default 20%), (5) If still wrong: SET enable_seqscan=off for testing, then understand why planner prefers seqscan, (6) Check: `SELECT * FROM pg_stats WHERE tablename='transactions' AND attname='<indexed_column>'` for histogram data quality."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Splunk alert is triggering 500 times per day on an event that is actually normal operation of a banking reconciliation job. The operations team is experiencing alert fatigue. What is the BEST solution?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Delete the Splunk alert to stop the noise", "feedback": "Incorrect. Deleting the alert removes monitoring for a real issue category — creates blind spot."},
      {"text": "Modify the Splunk search to exclude events from the reconciliation job (using sourcetype, host, or specific field values) while preserving alerting for genuine incidents", "feedback": "Correct. Alert fatigue is solved by improving alert precision, not by disabling monitoring. Exclude known-good events using specific identifiers."},
      {"text": "Acknowledge all 500 alerts daily to mark them as read", "feedback": "Incorrect. Manual acknowledgment is not a solution — it's a daily burden that leads to real alerts being missed among the noise."},
      {"text": "Increase the alert threshold to fire only when 1000 events occur per day", "feedback": "Incorrect. Raising threshold based on current noise level may mask future real incidents."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Alert precision: alert on what matters, exclude what's known-good. Never delete alerts to stop noise.",
    "explanation": "Alert tuning approaches: (1) `sourcetype=app_log NOT (process=reconciliation_job)` — exclude specific process, (2) `| where NOT match(message, 'Reconciliation completed')` — exclude specific message pattern, (3) Add time-based filter: `| where date_hour>=23 OR date_hour<=1` if job only runs at midnight, (4) Create separate low-priority alert for reconciliation job completion, (5) Document in runbook: 'Alert fires during reconciliation window — expected behavior', (6) Alert quality metric: aim for <5% false positive rate for actionable alerts."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking server running RHEL 7 shows that `/proc/sys/vm/swappiness` is set to 60. The server runs Oracle Database and is experiencing occasional performance issues. What should the swappiness be set to for an Oracle production database server?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Keep at 60 — this is the optimal Linux default", "feedback": "Incorrect. Default 60 is for general-purpose Linux. Oracle has specific recommendations."},
      {"text": "Set to 10 or lower — Oracle recommends minimizing swap usage for database servers as swapping SGA pages causes severe performance degradation", "feedback": "Correct. Oracle recommends vm.swappiness=10 (or even 1) for database servers. SGA/PGA should stay in physical RAM. Swapping database memory = catastrophic I/O latency."},
      {"text": "Set to 100 to maximize memory utilization through aggressive swapping", "feedback": "Incorrect. Swappiness=100 makes kernel aggressively swap — exactly opposite of what Oracle needs."},
      {"text": "Disable swap entirely by setting swappiness to 0", "feedback": "Incorrect. Swappiness=0 is too aggressive — kernel won't swap even when genuinely needed, risking OOM kill of Oracle processes."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Database servers need SGA in RAM always. Swap = disk-speed database access.",
    "explanation": "Oracle Linux tuning: (1) vm.swappiness=10 in /etc/sysctl.conf: sysctl -w vm.swappiness=10, (2) Check current swap usage: free -m, vmstat -s | grep swap, (3) If Oracle SGA is swapped: major performance crisis — check: cat /proc/<smon_pid>/smaps | grep Swap, (4) HugeTLB pages: for large SGA, use Huge Pages to prevent SGA from being swapped (MAP_SHARED huge pages are not swappable), (5) Configure: vm.nr_hugepages = SGA_size_in_bytes / hugepage_size."
  },
  {
    "question": "A newly deployed banking application in Docker shows that it works correctly in development but in production, the container cannot connect to the database which is running on the host machine. The connection string uses 'localhost'. What is the issue?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Docker needs privileged mode to access host network services", "feedback": "Incorrect. Privileged mode gives hardware access, not host service access. It's also a security risk."},
      {"text": "Inside a container, 'localhost' refers to the container itself, not the host. Use host.docker.internal (Docker Desktop) or the host's actual IP/docker bridge IP (172.17.0.1) instead", "feedback": "Correct. Container networking namespace is isolated. 'localhost' inside container = container's loopback (127.0.0.1), not the host. The DB on the host is accessible via host.docker.internal or the docker0 bridge gateway IP."},
      {"text": "The container needs to be in the same Docker network as the database container", "feedback": "Incorrect. The DB is on the HOST (not in Docker), so container network isn't the issue."},
      {"text": "Expose port 5432 in the Dockerfile to allow the container to access the host database", "feedback": "Incorrect. EXPOSE in Dockerfile exposes container ports, not connects to host ports."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Network namespace isolation: container 'localhost' ≠ host 'localhost'.",
    "explanation": "Docker host connectivity: (1) On Linux: use `ip addr show docker0` to get docker0 bridge IP (typically 172.17.0.1) — use this as DB host, (2) Docker Desktop (Mac/Windows): use `host.docker.internal` as the host DNS name, (3) Or: run container with --network=host (Linux only) — container shares host network namespace, localhost works, (4) Production recommendation: don't run DB on host for containerized apps — run DB in container or use managed DB service, (5) Update connection string: jdbc:postgresql://host.docker.internal:5432/bankdb."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle database alert log shows: 'Checkpoint not complete' appearing every 3 minutes. The database has 4 redo log groups each of 100MB size. The database generates approximately 500MB of redo per hour. What should be done?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Add more CPU to the server to speed up checkpointing", "feedback": "Incorrect. Checkpoint not complete is about redo log cycling, not CPU capacity."},
      {"text": "Add more redo log groups or increase the size of redo log files to reduce log switch frequency and give DBWr time to complete checkpoints", "feedback": "Correct. When redo log switches happen faster than DBWR can write dirty buffers to disk (checkpoint), Oracle waits with 'checkpoint not complete'. More/larger logs = more time between switches."},
      {"text": "Reduce FAST_START_MTTR_TARGET to force more frequent checkpoints", "feedback": "Incorrect. More frequent checkpoints mean MORE log switches, worsening the problem."},
      {"text": "Increase log_buffer parameter to buffer more redo in memory", "feedback": "Incorrect. Log buffer affects redo generation, not checkpoint completion speed."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Checkpoint not complete = redo logs cycling faster than DBWR checkpoints. More log space = more time.",
    "explanation": "Calculation: 500MB redo/hour ÷ 4 groups × 100MB = log switch every (100MB/(500/60MB per minute)) = every ~12 minutes. If checkpoint can't complete in 12 minutes, 'checkpoint not complete' appears. Fix: (1) Add more redo groups: ALTER DATABASE ADD LOGFILE GROUP 5 '/oracle/redo05.log' SIZE 500M, (2) Increase existing log size (requires recreating logs), (3) Monitor: SELECT group#, bytes/1024/1024 mb, members, status FROM v$log, (4) FAST_START_MTTR_TARGET: setting to 300 (5 min) tells DBWR to checkpoint more frequently — actually helps here by keeping checkpoint closer to current."
  },
  {
    "question": "During a routine security audit, it is found that the production WebLogic Admin Console is accessible from the public internet on port 7001. The banking application runs on port 443. What is the security risk and immediate action?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "No risk — WebLogic Admin Console has its own authentication mechanism", "feedback": "Incorrect. Exposing admin interfaces to the internet creates attack surface regardless of authentication. Brute force, CVE exploitation, and zero-day risks apply."},
      {"text": "Critical risk — WebLogic Admin Console has historical CVEs (CVE-2020-14882, etc.) that allow pre-authentication RCE. Immediately restrict port 7001 to trusted management IPs only via firewall/ACL", "feedback": "Correct. WebLogic admin port has multiple critical CVEs including pre-authentication remote code execution. Public exposure is a P1 security risk in banking environments."},
      {"text": "Low risk — change the default credentials to mitigate the exposure", "feedback": "Incorrect. Many WebLogic CVEs bypass authentication entirely. Strong passwords don't protect against pre-auth exploits."},
      {"text": "Disable WebLogic Admin Console since it's not needed for application operation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Admin Console is needed for management operations. The fix is network restriction, not disabling."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Admin interfaces should NEVER be internet-exposed. Always restrict to management networks.",
    "explanation": "Immediate actions: (1) Firewall rule: block public access to port 7001/7002 — allow only from management/bastion IP range, (2) Patch WebLogic to latest PSU — WebLogic CVEs are actively exploited, (3) Check access logs: has port 7001 been accessed from unexpected IPs? (4) Enable WebLogic admin channel on separate port bound only to management interface, (5) Implement bastion host / VPN requirement for admin access, (6) Regular: run WebLogic Security Configuration Checker, subscribe to Oracle Security Alerts."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production Linux server shows 100% inode usage on /var despite disk space being available (70% free). Application log writes are failing. What is causing this and what is the fix?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The disk has bad sectors causing inode table corruption", "feedback": "Incorrect. Bad sectors would show filesystem errors, not simply 100% inode usage with available disk space."},
      {"text": "The filesystem has run out of inodes — too many small files have been created, exhausting the fixed inode table even though disk space remains", "feedback": "Correct. Each file requires one inode. Inode count is fixed at filesystem creation. /var full of small files (e.g., session files, cache files, log rotation files) can exhaust inodes while disk space remains."},
      {"text": "Files larger than inode size cannot be created", "feedback": "Incorrect. Inode size relates to metadata storage, not file size limits."},
      {"text": "The OS needs to be rebooted to refresh the inode table", "feedback": "Incorrect. Inodes are persistent filesystem structures — reboot doesn't release them."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "df -h shows space available, df -i shows inodes. Two different resources can both be exhausted.",
    "explanation": "Diagnosis: `df -i /var` — shows inode usage. Fix: (1) Find directory with most files: `for d in /var/*; do echo \"$d: $(ls $d | wc -l) files\"; done | sort -t: -k2 -rn`, (2) `find /var -maxdepth 5 -type d -exec sh -c 'echo $(find {} -maxdepth 1 -type f | wc -l) {}' \\; | sort -rn | head`, (3) Clean up: remove session files, PHP session files, temp files, (4) Long-term: increase inode count requires reformatting (with -N or -i option for mke2fs), (5) Alternatively: move high-file-count directories to a separate filesystem."
  },
  {
    "question": "An AppDynamics alert fires for 'Slow Database Query' showing a query taking 45 seconds. The DBA checks the query and sees it was fast (0.5s) yesterday. The table has 50 million rows. Today, `EXPLAIN` shows 'Full Table Scan'. What changed most likely?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "AppDynamics threshold was lowered from 60 seconds to 30 seconds", "feedback": "Incorrect. Threshold change affects alerting, not actual query performance."},
      {"text": "An index on the queried column was dropped, or table statistics changed significantly causing the optimizer to choose a different execution plan", "feedback": "Correct. Query going from index scan to full table scan on 50M rows = either index dropped, or stale statistics causing optimizer to choose wrong plan, or a query hint was changed."},
      {"text": "The database server was upgraded to a new version that deprecated the index type", "feedback": "Incorrect. Index type deprecation would show in DB upgrade notes and cause index errors, not plan changes."},
      {"text": "AppDynamics is capturing a slow cold-start query, not a real performance regression", "feedback": "Incorrect. Cold start affects single execution — AppDynamics shows 45 seconds consistently, not a one-time event."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Full scan where index scan was used = index missing or optimizer not choosing it.",
    "explanation": "Investigation: (1) `SHOW INDEX FROM table_name` (MySQL) or `SELECT * FROM dba_indexes WHERE table_name='...'` (Oracle) — verify index exists, (2) If index missing: check who dropped it (audit trail), recreate, (3) If index exists: statistics issue — ANALYZE TABLE / ANALYZE (Oracle), (4) Oracle: `SELECT last_analyzed FROM dba_tables WHERE table_name='...'`, (5) Force plan: `/*+ INDEX(t idx_name) */` hint as temporary measure while fixing root cause, (6) Check: was there a bulk load, partition exchange, or mass delete/insert yesterday that invalidated statistics?"
  },
  {
    "question": "A Kubernetes Ingress for a banking portal is returning 502 Bad Gateway. The pods behind the ingress are running and responding to `kubectl exec` health checks. What should be investigated next?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Check if the pod's containerPort matches the Service's targetPort", "feedback": "Correct. 502 from Ingress = Ingress can reach the Service but Service cannot forward to the pod. Port mismatch between Service's targetPort and pod's containerPort is a common cause."},
      {"text": "Restart the Ingress controller pod", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting without investigation could cause a brief outage. Diagnose first."},
      {"text": "Increase the pod's CPU limit to handle the traffic", "feedback": "Incorrect. CPU limits affect performance, not 502 connectivity errors."},
      {"text": "Check DNS resolution for the Ingress hostname", "feedback": "Incorrect. 502 means the Ingress controller received the request but couldn't proxy to backend — DNS is not the issue at this stage."}
    ],
    "answer": 0,
    "hint": "502 = Ingress reached Service, Service failed to reach pod. Check Service → Pod connectivity.",
    "explanation": "502 debugging path: (1) `kubectl describe ingress <name>` — check backend service and port, (2) `kubectl describe service <name>` — check selector labels and targetPort, (3) `kubectl get endpoints <service-name>` — should show pod IPs. If empty, selector labels don't match pod labels, (4) Port check: Service targetPort must match pod's containerPort (not necessarily the same number — can use port names), (5) `kubectl exec <pod> -- curl localhost:<container-port>` — verify pod actually serves on that port, (6) Check Ingress controller logs: kubectl logs -n ingress-nginx <controller-pod>."
  },
  {
    "question": "During a banking application's peak period, the `top` command shows a Java process with 450% CPU utilization on a 8-core server. `jstack` thread dump shows hundreds of threads in RUNNABLE state, all working on HTTP request processing. What does this indicate?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The JVM is in a garbage collection storm consuming CPU", "feedback": "Incorrect. GC storm shows threads in GC-related states. Hundreds of RUNNABLE threads processing HTTP = legitimate high concurrency."},
      {"text": "The application is handling more concurrent requests than designed, with threads actively processing — potential CPU saturation from legitimate high load or a DoS condition", "feedback": "Correct. RUNNABLE threads on HTTP processing with 450% CPU (56% of 8 cores) = high but not impossible load. Could be legitimate traffic spike, runaway client, or DoS. Investigate request rate vs normal."},
      {"text": "The WebLogic thread pool is deadlocked causing CPU spin", "feedback": "Incorrect. Deadlock would show threads in BLOCKED/WAITING state, not RUNNABLE."},
      {"text": "The server needs more CPUs to handle the load", "feedback": "Incorrect. While scaling might be needed, first determine if this is legitimate load or abnormal (DoS, bug)."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "RUNNABLE threads = actively working. Is this legitimate traffic or something wrong?",
    "explanation": "Investigation: (1) Check application request rate: access logs, AppDynamics BT throughput — is requests/sec normal or spiked?, (2) Check source IPs: `awk '{print $1}' access.log | sort | uniq -c | sort -rn | head` — is one IP hammering the server? (3) Normal: implement auto-scaling, (4) DoS: implement rate limiting at load balancer/WAF level, (5) Bug: identify if requests are taking longer than normal (each thread blocks for longer), (6) `jstack` analysis: are all threads doing useful work or waiting on same resource?"
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application reports 'ORA-12541: TNS:no listener' when connecting to Oracle from a new application server. The DBA confirms the listener is running on the DB server. What should be tested first?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Restart the Oracle listener on the DB server", "feedback": "Incorrect. Listener is confirmed running. Restarting it doesn't fix connectivity from a new server."},
      {"text": "Test network connectivity from the new application server to the DB server on the listener port using telnet or nc", "feedback": "Correct. ORA-12541 means the application server cannot reach the Oracle listener. This is a network/firewall issue between the new app server and DB server — not a listener configuration issue."},
      {"text": "Modify the tnsnames.ora on the application server", "feedback": "Incorrect. tnsnames.ora configuration is step 2. First confirm basic network connectivity to port 1521."},
      {"text": "Increase Oracle's max processes parameter to allow more connections", "feedback": "Incorrect. max processes affects connection limits, not listener accessibility from new servers."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "TNS:no listener from a NEW server = connectivity issue. Test basic network first.",
    "explanation": "Troubleshooting ORA-12541 from new server: (1) `telnet <db-server> 1521` or `nc -zv <db-server> 1521` — tests basic TCP connectivity, (2) If fails: firewall rule missing for new server's IP to DB server port 1521, (3) If succeeds: tnsnames.ora or connection string issue, (4) `tnsping <tns_alias>` from app server — tests TNS resolution, (5) Firewall fix: add new app server IP to firewall rule for DB server port 1521, (6) Verify listener: lsnrctl status on DB server — should show service registered."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application's SLA requires 99.95% uptime. The operations team wants to implement planned maintenance windows of 4 hours per month. Is this compatible with the SLA?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Yes, planned maintenance windows are excluded from SLA calculations", "feedback": "Incorrect. This depends on the SLA agreement. Not all SLAs exclude planned maintenance — this must be explicitly stated in the SLA terms."},
      {"text": "No — 99.95% uptime allows only 21.9 minutes of downtime per month (planned + unplanned). 4 hours of planned maintenance alone exceeds this", "feedback": "Correct. 99.95% of 30 days = 43,200 × 0.0005 = 21.6 minutes total downtime budget. 4 hours = 240 minutes >> 21.6 minutes. Either renegotiate SLA to include maintenance exclusion, or implement zero-downtime maintenance."},
      {"text": "Yes, because planned maintenance is less than 5% of monthly time", "feedback": "Incorrect. 4 hours/month is about 0.56% downtime, exceeding the 0.05% budget."},
      {"text": "Impossible to determine without knowing the time zone of the SLA", "feedback": "Incorrect. SLA percentage is based on total time, independent of time zone."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Calculate: 99.95% uptime → 0.05% downtime. What is 0.05% of 30 days in minutes?",
    "explanation": "SLA math: 30 days × 24 × 60 = 43,200 min. 0.05% = 21.6 min budget. Options: (1) Amend SLA to explicitly exclude planned maintenance windows (common practice: 'Excluding scheduled maintenance windows notified 5 days in advance'), (2) Implement zero-downtime deployment using blue-green or rolling updates, (3) Use rolling maintenance on cluster nodes (take one node down while others serve traffic), (4) Negotiate: 99.9% during maintenance months, 99.95% for remaining months, (5) Document maintenance exclusions in SLM agreement clearly."
  },
  {
    "question": "A team notices that a PostgreSQL table `bank_transactions` has `n_dead_tup` growing rapidly to 10 million despite autovacuum being enabled. `pg_stat_activity` shows autovacuum worker running on the table. What could prevent autovacuum from reclaiming dead tuples even while running?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Autovacuum has a bug in the current PostgreSQL version", "feedback": "Incorrect. Assuming a bug as root cause without evidence is incorrect troubleshooting approach."},
      {"text": "A long-running transaction or idle-in-transaction session is preventing vacuum from advancing the oldest transaction horizon, so dead tuples remain 'visible' to that old transaction", "feedback": "Correct. Vacuum cannot remove dead tuples that might be needed by any open transaction. The oldest transaction's xmin prevents cleanup even if autovacuum is actively running."},
      {"text": "The table is too large for autovacuum and needs manual VACUUM FULL", "feedback": "Incorrect. Table size doesn't prevent autovacuum from running — it just takes longer. VACUUM FULL also blocks other sessions and is rarely needed."},
      {"text": "The dead tuple threshold needs to be lowered to trigger more frequent vacuum", "feedback": "Incorrect. With 10M dead tuples, threshold is already exceeded — vacuum is running. The issue is why it can't CLEAN them."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Vacuum running but not cleaning = something is blocking the cleanup horizon.",
    "explanation": "Key concept: PostgreSQL MVCC uses transaction IDs. Vacuum can only remove dead tuples with xmax < oldest_active_xid. Check: (1) SELECT pid, usename, state, xact_start, query FROM pg_stat_activity WHERE state != 'idle' ORDER BY xact_start — find old transactions, (2) SELECT slot_name, xmin FROM pg_replication_slots — inactive slots hold xmin forever, (3) Fix: terminate old transactions, drop inactive replication slots, (4) Monitor: SELECT age(datfrozenxid) FROM pg_database — tracks oldest unfrozen transaction."
  },
  {
    "question": "During a production incident, an on-call engineer shares their screen and accidentally exposes database credentials visible in a config file. The call recording is saved. What is the correct incident response action?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Continue with the incident and rotate credentials after the incident is resolved", "feedback": "Incorrect. Credentials should be rotated as soon as possible after exposure, not delayed. An exposed credential is a security incident running in parallel."},
      {"text": "Immediately rotate the exposed database credentials, restrict access to the recording, and raise a security incident to assess if any unauthorized access occurred using those credentials", "feedback": "Correct. Credential exposure is a security incident. Rotate immediately, secure the recording (PII/credentials handling), investigate if credentials were used by unauthorized parties."},
      {"text": "Delete the call recording to prevent credential exposure", "feedback": "Incorrect. Deleting evidence may violate regulatory requirements and incident investigation needs. Restrict access instead."},
      {"text": "Only rotate credentials if the call was with external parties", "feedback": "Incorrect. Internal exposure is also a security concern — insider threats are a real risk in banking."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Credential exposure = security incident. Rotate immediately, investigate impact.",
    "explanation": "Credential exposure response: (1) Immediate: rotate the database password, (2) Assess: who was on the call? Internal only or external?, (3) Investigate: review DB audit logs for any access with the exposed credentials from unexpected sources, (4) Recording: mark as restricted, notify legal/compliance — may require retention per regulatory requirements but access must be controlled, (5) Report: raise security incident per information security policy, (6) Prevention: use vault solutions (HashiCorp Vault, CyberArk) so credentials are never in config files."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production Oracle database is running out of undo space and showing ORA-30036: unable to extend segment in undo tablespace. The undo tablespace is set to 20GB with AUTOEXTEND ON but the datafile is at maximum size. What are the options?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Restart the database to clear all undo segments", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting is extremely disruptive and doesn't fix the root cause. Undo grows back immediately."},
      {"text": "Add a new datafile to the undo tablespace, and identify long-running transactions generating excessive undo", "feedback": "Correct. Adding datafile immediately relieves pressure. Simultaneously find and address long-running transactions or bulk operations generating excessive undo."},
      {"text": "Switch to the SYSTEM tablespace for undo temporarily", "feedback": "Incorrect. SYSTEM tablespace is for Oracle's internal objects. Using it for undo is not supported and causes serious issues."},
      {"text": "Reduce UNDO_RETENTION to free up space faster", "feedback": "Incorrect. Reducing UNDO_RETENTION causes ORA-01555 for long-running queries. It doesn't immediately free existing undo used by active transactions."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Undo full: short-term = add space, medium-term = find and fix excessive undo generators.",
    "explanation": "Immediate: ALTER TABLESPACE UNDOTBS1 ADD DATAFILE '/oracle/undo02.dbf' SIZE 10G AUTOEXTEND ON MAXSIZE 30G. Then: (1) Find excessive undo generators: SELECT s.sid, s.username, t.used_ublk*8192/1024/1024 mb_undo FROM v$session s, v$transaction t WHERE s.taddr = t.addr ORDER BY used_ublk DESC, (2) Is there a bulk UPDATE/DELETE without commits? Optimize to batch with COMMIT every N rows, (3) Long-running queries: check if batch job can be rescheduled, (4) Monitor: SELECT tablespace_name, used_space, tablespace_size FROM dba_undo_extents."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Linux server's `free -m` shows: total=64000, used=63500, free=500, shared=0, buff/cache=40000. Is the server running out of memory?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Yes — only 500MB is free, which is critically low for a banking server", "feedback": "Incorrect. 'free' in the first line of older `free` output doesn't account for reclaimable buffer/cache."},
      {"text": "No — the 40GB in buff/cache is reclaimable by the OS when applications need memory. Effective free memory ≈ 500+40000=40500MB", "feedback": "Correct. Linux uses available RAM for disk cache (buff/cache) which is reclaimable. The 'available' column in modern `free` shows this correctly. High cache usage is normal and beneficial."},
      {"text": "Cannot determine without checking swap usage", "feedback": "Incorrect. The buff/cache clarification is sufficient to determine memory availability without needing swap data."},
      {"text": "Yes — buff/cache being high means the OS is struggling with I/O", "feedback": "Incorrect. High buff/cache is normal and good — it means the OS is efficiently caching frequently accessed data."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Linux uses free RAM as disk cache. This cache is reclaimable — it's not 'used' memory.",
    "explanation": "Modern `free -m` output: (1) The 'available' column directly shows reclaimable memory = free + reclaimable cache, (2) If available > application needs: no memory pressure, (3) Memory pressure indicators: high swap usage (`swapon --show`), high oom_kill events (`dmesg | grep -i 'oom'`), application OOM kills, (4) Commands: `free -h` (human readable), `vmstat -s | grep memory`, (5) Per-process: `cat /proc/<pid>/status | grep VmRSS` for resident memory, (6) If genuinely low: check for memory leaks with `ps aux --sort=-%mem | head`."
  },
  {
    "question": "A WebLogic deployment fails with: 'java.lang.OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace'. The deployment was previously working with a smaller application. The new deployment is significantly larger with many more classes. What should be adjusted?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase -Xmx to allocate more heap for class loading", "feedback": "Incorrect. Metaspace is not part of the Java heap (from Java 8+). -Xmx doesn't affect Metaspace."},
      {"text": "Add JVM argument -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m (or larger) to increase the Metaspace limit", "feedback": "Correct. From Java 8+, class metadata is stored in Metaspace (native memory, not heap). Larger applications with more classes/methods need more Metaspace. Default is unlimited but OS-limited."},
      {"text": "Add more physical RAM to the server", "feedback": "Partially relevant but not the direct fix. MaxMetaspaceSize must be explicitly set or Metaspace can grow unbounded."},
      {"text": "Enable class data sharing (CDS) to reduce Metaspace usage", "feedback": "Partially valid optimization but not the immediate fix for OutOfMemoryError: Metaspace during deployment."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Metaspace stores class metadata. Large applications need more. -Xmx doesn't help.",
    "explanation": "Metaspace sizing: (1) Default: unbounded (grows until OS OOM), (2) Set: -XX:MetaspaceSize=256m -XX:MaxMetaspaceSize=512m, (3) Monitor: jstat -gcmetacapacity <pid> shows MetaUsed, MetaMax, (4) Causes of large Metaspace: many classes (large EAR), heavy use of reflection, dynamic proxy generation, bytecode manipulation (Hibernate, Spring), (5) Metaspace leaks: classloaders not garbage collected due to references — common in app servers with hot deployments, (6) WebLogic hot deploy: old ClassLoader not GCed = Metaspace grows with each redeployment."
  },
  {
    "question": "An SRE team wants to establish SLOs (Service Level Objectives) for a new banking payment API. The API currently has no SLAs. What is the correct approach to define meaningful SLOs?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Set SLO at 99.999% uptime immediately to demonstrate commitment to quality", "feedback": "Incorrect. Setting aggressive SLOs without data makes them either impossible to meet or too easy. SLOs must be based on data and business need."},
      {"text": "Baseline current performance metrics over 30-90 days, define error budget, align with business stakeholders on acceptable service levels, then set achievable SLOs with monitoring", "feedback": "Correct. SLOs require: current performance baseline, business requirements (what does failure cost?), technical feasibility assessment, and agreement between engineering and business on the error budget."},
      {"text": "Copy SLOs from a similar banking application in the industry", "feedback": "Incorrect. SLOs must reflect your system's architecture, dependencies, and business requirements — copy-paste creates misaligned expectations."},
      {"text": "Set SLOs equal to current SLAs to avoid any violations", "feedback": "Incorrect. SLOs should be more stringent than SLAs (SLO = warning level, SLA = contractual obligation). If SLO=SLA, no early warning."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "SLOs: data-driven, business-aligned, technically achievable. Not aspirational or arbitrary.",
    "explanation": "SLO definition process: (1) Instrument: add metrics (latency percentiles, error rate, availability), (2) Baseline: 30-90 days of data — what is current P99 latency, error rate?, (3) Business alignment: what latency/error rate causes customer impact? Business must define acceptable thresholds, (4) Error budget: 100% - SLO% = allowed errors, (5) Example: If payment API currently has 0.1% error rate and business needs <0.5%, SLO=99.5% (0.5% errors), SLA=99% (1% errors), (6) SLI (indicator): actual metric. SLO (objective): target. SLA (agreement): contractual with consequences."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application on Linux shows the following in cron: `0 2 * * * /opt/app/cleanup.sh`. The cleanup script sometimes fails silently without any notification. What mechanism can be added to ensure failures are detected?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Add `set -e` to the cleanup.sh script", "feedback": "Partially correct — set -e exits on error, but doesn't add notification."},
      {"text": "Redirect cron output to a log file and add error checking: `2>&1 | tee /var/log/cleanup.log`, and configure the script to email on failure using `mail` command or monitoring integration", "feedback": "Correct. Cron by default discards stdout/stderr (or emails root if MAILTO is set). Add logging, error trapping (trap ERR), and notification to make failures visible."},
      {"text": "Run the script every 30 minutes instead of daily to detect failures faster", "feedback": "Incorrect. More frequent runs don't help detect failures from individual runs — monitoring does."},
      {"text": "Change cron to systemd timer which provides better logging", "feedback": "Correct as an improvement but not a complete answer — systemd timers with journald logging + alerting is good, but cron with proper logging also works."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Silent failures = no alerting on failure. Add logging + notification to make failures visible.",
    "explanation": "Robust cron job design: (1) `MAILTO=ops-team@bank.com` at top of crontab — sends output to email, (2) In script: `exec &>> /var/log/cleanup.log` — log all output, (3) Error trapping: `trap 'echo FAILED at line $LINENO; send_alert' ERR`, (4) Exit code check: `cleanup.sh || send_alert 'cleanup failed'`, (5) Monitoring integration: push success/failure to monitoring system (Nagios passive check, Prometheus pushgateway), (6) Modern approach: systemd timer with `OnFailure=` directive to trigger alert service. Heartbeat monitoring: alert if job DOESN'T run (deadman's switch)."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking Java application shows performance degradation during business hours. JVM logs show frequent 'Full GC (Ergonomics)' events pausing the JVM for 5-10 seconds each. The JVM uses G1GC. What is likely causing frequent Full GC with G1GC?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "G1GC cannot handle banking applications and should be replaced with CMS", "feedback": "Incorrect. G1GC is recommended for banking applications. The issue is configuration or memory, not the collector choice."},
      {"text": "G1GC's concurrent collection is not completing before old generation fills up — possibly due to large objects bypassing young generation or humongous object allocation", "feedback": "Correct. 'Full GC (Ergonomics)' in G1GC means G1 couldn't keep up. Causes: humongous allocations (objects > G1 region size), old gen filling too fast, heap too small for allocation rate."},
      {"text": "Full GC is normal for G1GC and 5-10 second pauses are expected", "feedback": "Incorrect. G1GC is designed for predictable, short pauses. 5-10 second Full GCs indicate a problem."},
      {"text": "The server's physical memory is insufficient for the JVM heap size", "feedback": "Incorrect. Insufficient physical memory causes swap usage, which indirectly causes GC issues, but the direct cause is G1GC configuration."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "G1GC Full GC = concurrent collection failed. Humongous objects and heap sizing are common causes.",
    "explanation": "G1GC Full GC causes: (1) Humongous objects (> 50% of G1 region size): go straight to old gen, bypass young gen, cause region fragmentation, (2) Allocation rate exceeds G1's collection throughput, (3) Fix humongous objects: increase G1 region size: -XX:G1HeapRegionSize=16m, (4) Tune: -XX:G1NewSizePercent=40 (increase young gen), -XX:G1MaxNewSizePercent=60, (5) Increase heap: -Xmx, (6) Monitor: `jstat -gcutil <pid> 1000` — watch O (old gen %) approaching 100% triggers Full GC, (7) GC log analysis: `-Xlog:gc*:file=gc.log:time,uptime:filecount=5,filesize=20m`."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production incident is raised: users report intermittent 'Session Expired' errors on the banking portal even though they just logged in. The portal uses WebLogic cluster with session replication. What should be investigated?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase the HTTP session timeout in web.xml", "feedback": "Incorrect. The session expires immediately after login, not due to timeout. Increasing timeout doesn't fix replication issues."},
      {"text": "Check WebLogic cluster replication: whether the session fails to replicate to the secondary server before the load balancer routes the next request there", "feedback": "Correct. Session expires = session doesn't exist on the server handling the next request. In a cluster, if session replication fails/is slow, the secondary server doesn't have the session."},
      {"text": "The users' browsers are clearing cookies between requests", "feedback": "Incorrect. Browser clearing cookies mid-session would log users out entirely, not cause 'Session Expired' specifically."},
      {"text": "The database session table is corrupted", "feedback": "Incorrect. If using DB-backed sessions, corruption would cause all sessions to fail, not intermittent ones."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Intermittent session loss in cluster = replication lag or failure between nodes.",
    "explanation": "WebLogic session replication debugging: (1) Check cluster configuration: in-memory replication vs JDBC replication, (2) In-memory: verify cluster heartbeat — `clustersecret` must match on all nodes, (3) JDBC: check DB table used for session replication, (4) Network: cluster replication uses a separate channel — check firewall rules between managed servers, (5) Load balancer: enable sticky sessions (session persistence) as mitigation while fixing replication, (6) Monitor: WebLogic cluster > Monitoring > Servers — check replication health, (7) Test: simulate failover, verify session survives."
  },
  {
    "question": "A DevOps team deploys a banking microservice using Helm chart. The deployment succeeds but the pods are failing health checks. `kubectl describe pod` shows: 'Liveness probe failed: HTTP probe failed with statuscode: 404'. The service path in the application is `/api/v2/health` but the Helm values show `livenessProbe.path: /health`. What should be done?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Change the application's health endpoint to /health to match the probe configuration", "feedback": "Incorrect. Changing application code to match a wrong configuration is backwards. The configuration should match the application."},
      {"text": "Update the Helm values to set livenessProbe.path: /api/v2/health and redeploy", "feedback": "Correct. Helm chart livenessProbe path must match the actual application's health endpoint path. Update values.yaml and redeploy."},
      {"text": "Disable the liveness probe temporarily while investigating", "feedback": "Incorrect. Disabling liveness probes prevents Kubernetes from restarting truly unhealthy pods — bad practice in production."},
      {"text": "The application needs to expose both /health and /api/v2/health paths", "feedback": "Incorrect. The simplest fix is to correct the probe path in the Helm chart to match the actual endpoint."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Probe path ≠ actual health endpoint. Fix the configuration to match the application.",
    "explanation": "Helm chart probe configuration: in values.yaml: livenessProbe: { path: /api/v2/health, port: 8080, initialDelaySeconds: 30, periodSeconds: 10 }. Steps: (1) Verify correct path: `kubectl exec <pod> -- curl localhost:8080/api/v2/health` — should return 200, (2) Update values.yaml with correct path, (3) `helm upgrade <release> <chart> -f values.yaml`, (4) Best practice: test liveness/readiness probes in local dev before deploying, (5) Also verify: port, scheme (HTTP vs HTTPS), initialDelaySeconds (must be longer than app startup time)."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking organization's Problem Management team identifies that 60% of all P1 incidents in the last quarter were caused by unauthorized changes made outside the change management process. What ITIL improvement should be recommended?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Implement more frequent training on ITIL change management processes", "feedback": "Partially correct but training alone doesn't prevent unauthorized changes."},
      {"text": "Implement technical controls: restrict production access to authorized change tickets only (CAB approval gates), integrate change records with deployment pipeline, and add unauthorized change detection monitoring", "feedback": "Correct. Training is insufficient alone. Technical controls that make unauthorized changes impossible or immediately detectable are more effective: pipeline gates, prod access tied to change tickets, automated change detection."},
      {"text": "Fire the team members who made unauthorized changes", "feedback": "Incorrect. Punitive approach without process improvement doesn't prevent future occurrences — other team members may do the same."},
      {"text": "Increase the number of CAB meetings per week to process changes faster", "feedback": "Incorrect. The issue is changes bypassing CAB, not CAB being too slow (though this could be a contributing factor)."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Unauthorized changes at 60% = process gap + inadequate technical controls. Fix both.",
    "explanation": "Preventive controls: (1) Production access tied to change management: deployment tools (Jenkins, Ansible) require a valid change ticket number as parameter, (2) Just-in-time access: production SSH access granted only during approved maintenance windows, (3) Change detection: automated comparison of production configuration against known-good baseline — alert on any drift, (4) PAM (Privileged Access Management) solution: all production commands logged and tied to change records, (5) Also address root cause: if CAB is too slow and teams bypass it, expedite process for routine changes — too many unauthorized changes = process too bureaucratic."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application uses Oracle for OLTP. DBAs notice that the `SYSAUX` tablespace is growing rapidly, now at 98%. What is the most common cause of SYSAUX growth?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Business application data is being stored in SYSAUX", "feedback": "Incorrect. Application data should not be in SYSAUX. If it is, that's a configuration error but not the common growth cause."},
      {"text": "AWR (Automatic Workload Repository) and ASH (Active Session History) data accumulating due to default 30-day retention without space management", "feedback": "Correct. SYSAUX is the primary tablespace for Oracle's instrumentation features: AWR snapshots, ASH data, Statspack, EM repository. AWR retention of 30 days on a busy database generates significant data."},
      {"text": "The database has too many users created in the default tablespace", "feedback": "Incorrect. User objects in wrong tablespace affect that tablespace, not necessarily SYSAUX."},
      {"text": "Database auditing is writing too many records to SYSAUX", "feedback": "Incorrect. Standard auditing writes to AUD$ in SYSTEM tablespace. Unified auditing (12c+) uses AUDSYS schema in SYSAUX — this could be a factor but is secondary to AWR."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "SYSAUX is Oracle's infrastructure tablespace. AWR is the primary consumer on busy systems.",
    "explanation": "SYSAUX management: (1) Check space consumers: SELECT occupant_name, space_usage_kbytes/1024 mb FROM v$sysaux_occupants ORDER BY space_usage_kbytes DESC, (2) AWR is top consumer: reduce retention: EXECUTE DBMS_WORKLOAD_REPOSITORY.MODIFY_SNAPSHOT_SETTINGS(retention => 10*24*60, interval => 60) — reduce from 30 to 10 days, (3) Purge old AWR data: EXECUTE DBMS_WORKLOAD_REPOSITORY.DROP_SNAPSHOT_RANGE(low_snap_id => 1, high_snap_id => <old_snap>), (4) Add datafile: ALTER TABLESPACE SYSAUX ADD DATAFILE '/oracle/sysaux02.dbf' SIZE 5G, (5) Move non-critical occupants if possible."
  },
  {
    "question": "A senior engineer is reviewing a Kubernetes network policy and notices that all pods in the `banking-prod` namespace can communicate with all pods in the `banking-dev` namespace. What is the security risk and recommended fix?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "No risk — development data is not sensitive", "feedback": "Incorrect. In banking, development environments may have copies of masked production data, or a compromised dev pod could be used to pivot to prod."},
      {"text": "Lateral movement risk: a compromised pod in dev can access production services. Implement network policies to deny all cross-namespace traffic except explicitly approved paths", "feedback": "Correct. Unrestricted cross-namespace communication is a security risk (East-West attack). Zero-trust networking: deny all by default, allow only required paths with explicit NetworkPolicy rules."},
      {"text": "The network policy is only about bandwidth, not security", "feedback": "Incorrect. Kubernetes NetworkPolicy controls which pods can communicate — it is a security control."},
      {"text": "Rename namespaces so dev and prod don't communicate", "feedback": "Incorrect. Namespace names don't control traffic — NetworkPolicy rules do."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Default-allow network policy violates zero-trust security model in banking.",
    "explanation": "Kubernetes network isolation: (1) Default: all pods can communicate with all pods (no NetworkPolicy = allow all), (2) Implement default-deny: `spec: podSelector: {} policyTypes: [Ingress, Egress]` — blocks all traffic, (3) Explicitly allow: prod services only accept from other prod pods + specific dev test accounts, (4) Separate node pools for prod/dev for additional isolation, (5) Banking compliance: PCI-DSS requires network segmentation between CDE (cardholder data environment) and other environments, (6) Test with: `kubectl exec <pod> -- curl <cross-namespace-service>` — should fail after applying NetworkPolicy."
  },
  {
    "question": "A WebLogic managed server generates a heap dump automatically on OOM. The heap dump file is 15GB and the team needs to analyze it. Eclipse MAT on a laptop with 8GB RAM cannot open the file. What is the solution?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Truncate the heap dump file to 8GB to fit in RAM", "feedback": "Incorrect. Truncating the heap dump destroys data integrity — an incomplete heap dump is meaningless for analysis."},
      {"text": "Use Eclipse MAT's batch mode on a larger server, or use `jhat`, or parse with command-line tools like `jmap -histo` to get class histogram without loading full dump", "feedback": "Correct. Multiple approaches: (1) MAT batch mode on a server with 32GB+ RAM, (2) Online heap dump analysis services, (3) jmap -histo (if process is still running), (4) MAT's overview analysis that doesn't require full load."},
      {"text": "Delete the heap dump and trigger a new, smaller one by setting -XX:HeapDumpOnOutOfMemoryError on a server with less memory", "feedback": "Incorrect. A smaller server would also OOM. Deleting the only heap dump loses the evidence."},
      {"text": "Convert the heap dump to text format using hprof to make it readable", "feedback": "Incorrect. No standard tool converts binary hprof to text while preserving analysis capability. The binary format is required for analysis."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "15GB heap dump needs proportionally large analysis RAM. Use appropriate tools.",
    "explanation": "Large heap dump analysis: (1) MAT batch mode: `ParseHeapDump.sh heap.hprof org.eclipse.mat.api:suspects` — needs ~2x heap size in RAM (30GB), (2) Use a server with adequate RAM: cloud instance (128GB) for analysis, (3) MAT Overview: can generate leak suspects report without fully loading all objects, (4) jmap alternatives: `jmap -histo:live <pid>` if process still running — shows class histogram, (5) JDK Flight Recorder / Mission Control for ongoing analysis, (6) IBM Heap Analyzer for very large dumps with external file support, (7) Sampling profilers (async-profiler) generate much smaller profiles — use for future incidents."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application team needs to perform root cause analysis for an intermittent performance issue that occurs every few days and lasts 10-20 minutes. The issue doesn't recur in test environments. What is the BEST approach?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Wait for the next occurrence and manually investigate while the issue is happening", "feedback": "Partially correct but relying on manual intervention during a time-critical window is error-prone. Preparation is key."},
      {"text": "Implement continuous profiling and monitoring with automated data capture triggers: when latency exceeds threshold, automatically capture thread dumps, heap stats, network connections, and DB session data", "feedback": "Correct. For intermittent issues that don't reproduce, proactive data collection during the actual occurrence is the only reliable approach. Automated triggers ensure comprehensive capture without requiring manual intervention."},
      {"text": "Increase logging to DEBUG level permanently to capture all events", "feedback": "Incorrect. Permanent DEBUG logging in banking production creates I/O overhead, disk space issues, and security concerns (may log sensitive data)."},
      {"text": "Rebuild the application from scratch with better instrumentation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Rebuilding is extreme and time-consuming. Instrumentation can be added without rebuilding (APM agents, bytecode instrumentation)."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Intermittent, hard-to-reproduce issues need automated capture when they occur.",
    "explanation": "Automated capture strategy: (1) APM (AppDynamics/Dynatrace): configured to capture snapshots and thread dumps when transaction time exceeds threshold, (2) Custom trigger: script monitoring response time, when >5s threshold: `jstack <pid> > /tmp/thread_dump_$(date +%s).txt`, capture `netstat -an`, Oracle session snapshot, (3) JVM flags: -XX:+PrintGCDetails for GC correlation, -XX:+PrintSafepointStatistics for JVM pauses, (4) Enable Slow Query Log in DB during next occurrence, (5) Network capture: tcpdump on key interfaces with file rotation — 24h of captures ready to analyze, (6) Correlate all data after next occurrence."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle RAC database shows that one instance has significantly higher 'gc buffer busy acquire' and 'gc cr block 2-way' wait events than the other instances. What does this indicate in a RAC environment?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "One RAC node has a hardware problem causing slow block transfers", "feedback": "Partially relevant but the specific wait events have a more precise meaning."},
      {"text": "Cache Fusion is transferring data blocks between RAC instances frequently — possibly because multiple instances are accessing the same data blocks (hot blocks), causing inter-instance traffic", "feedback": "Correct. 'gc' wait events are Cache Fusion waits. gc buffer busy = current instance wants a block but another instance has it dirty. gc cr = consistent read block transfer. High values indicate hot blocks being shared across instances."},
      {"text": "The ASM diskgroup has unequal I/O distribution across instances", "feedback": "Incorrect. ASM I/O distribution issues cause disk I/O waits, not gc (global cache) wait events."},
      {"text": "The Oracle clusterware is misconfigured causing extra heartbeats", "feedback": "Incorrect. Clusterware misconfiguration causes cluster communication issues, not gc block wait events."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "gc = global cache. In RAC, global cache is how instances share blocks via interconnect.",
    "explanation": "Cache Fusion optimization: (1) Identify hot blocks: SELECT file#, block#, count(*) FROM v$gcspfmaster_info GROUP BY file#, block# ORDER BY 3 DESC, (2) Identify objects: SELECT owner, segment_name FROM dba_extents WHERE file_id=<file#> AND block_id=<block#>, (3) Solutions: a) Partition the hot table and pin partitions to specific instances (service-based routing), b) Application-level sharding: route user A's transactions to Instance 1, user B's to Instance 2, c) Index hot spot reduction: use reverse key index for sequences, (4) Monitor interconnect: ifconfig <interconnect_nic> — check errors/drops on interconnect."
  },
  {
    "question": "During a security review, an operations team discovers that application logs on a banking production server contain full credit card numbers in plaintext. The logs are shipped to Splunk and stored for 90 days. What should be the FIRST action?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Immediately purge all 90 days of logs from Splunk", "feedback": "Incorrect. Purging logs without regulatory guidance may violate audit requirements and destroy evidence needed for impact assessment. Legal/compliance must be involved first."},
      {"text": "Immediately notify the security team and compliance/legal, restrict access to the affected logs, and assess the scope of the exposure — how many cards, which logs, who has accessed the logs", "feedback": "Correct. PAN (Primary Account Number) exposure in logs is a PCI-DSS violation and potential data breach. Immediate actions: contain (restrict access), assess (scope), notify (compliance, legal, potentially regulators)."},
      {"text": "Fix the application logging to mask card numbers and deploy to production", "feedback": "Correct as a remediation step, but not the FIRST action. Contain and assess first."},
      {"text": "Ignore it if no external party has accessed the logs", "feedback": "Incorrect. PCI-DSS requires investigation and reporting of any PAN exposure, regardless of whether external access occurred."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "PCI data in logs = potential data breach. First: contain, assess, notify — not delete.",
    "explanation": "PCI-DSS incident response: (1) Contain: restrict log access immediately — only security team and investigators, (2) Assess: how far back do affected logs go? How many unique PANs? Who has Splunk access?, (3) Notify: security team, CISO, legal/compliance, (4) Regulatory: PCI-DSS breach notification requirements vary by country/card scheme, (5) Forensic preservation: don't modify logs — preserve for investigation, (6) Remediation: mask PAN in application (log4j PatternLayout masking, or application-level) before logging, (7) Splunk: implement data masking transforms to mask PAN in log data ingestion pipeline."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking team needs to implement blue-green deployment for their critical payment service. What is the PRIMARY benefit of blue-green over rolling deployment for this use case?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Blue-green uses less infrastructure than rolling deployment", "feedback": "Incorrect. Blue-green requires double the infrastructure (two full environments running simultaneously)."},
      {"text": "Blue-green allows instantaneous cutover and instantaneous rollback — if the green deployment has issues, traffic switches back to blue in seconds with zero redeployment needed", "feedback": "Correct. For payment services, zero-downtime cutover and instant rollback capability are critical. Blue-green achieves this via load balancer switch. Rolling deployment takes time to roll back."},
      {"text": "Blue-green eliminates the need for testing before deployment", "feedback": "Incorrect. Blue-green still requires thorough testing — the green environment is tested before traffic cutover."},
      {"text": "Blue-green is simpler to implement than rolling deployment", "feedback": "Incorrect. Blue-green requires maintaining two complete environments and managing the switch — typically more complex than rolling deployment."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Blue-green key value: instantaneous switch + instantaneous rollback. Why does that matter for payments?",
    "explanation": "Blue-green for banking payments: (1) Green environment is fully deployed and tested before any traffic, (2) Cutover: update load balancer to send 100% traffic to green (seconds), (3) Rollback: update LB back to blue (seconds, no redeployment), (4) Testing: run smoke tests against green with production database (or shadow DB) before cutover, (5) Database migrations: must be backward compatible with blue (can't have schema changes that break blue), (6) Session handling: users with active sessions on blue need graceful handling during switch, (7) Canary within blue-green: send 5% to green first, verify, then switch 100%."
  },
  {
    "question": "A batch job on a Linux server runs for 8 hours every night. On Tuesday it ran normally in 8 hours. On Wednesday it ran for 14 hours. `top` showed normal CPU. The DBA found the batch job spent most time in 'db file sequential read' wait. What changed?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The batch job code was changed on Tuesday night", "feedback": "Possible but need to check this. The DBA finding high 'db file sequential read' is a better clue."},
      {"text": "An index used by the batch job's SQL was recently dropped or made unusable — forcing full scans where index lookups were used, increasing disk reads", "feedback": "Correct. 'db file sequential read' is an index block read wait. If index was dropped, Oracle may now use full scans (which would be 'db file scattered read'). But if the index is still there but reads more blocks due to fragmentation or statistics issue, sequential reads increase."},
      {"text": "The database server's CPU was throttled by the hypervisor on Wednesday", "feedback": "Incorrect. The question states CPU was normal from top."},
      {"text": "More users were active Wednesday night causing lock contention with the batch job", "feedback": "Incorrect. Lock contention shows as enq: TX or similar wait events, not 'db file sequential read'."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "db file sequential read = random I/O (index). Dramatic increase means more index blocks to read or worse access path.",
    "explanation": "Investigation: (1) AWR comparison: Tuesday vs Wednesday — compare SQL execution plans for the batch's SQLs, (2) Check if statistics on batch tables were regenerated: SELECT last_analyzed FROM dba_tables WHERE owner='BATCH_USER', (3) If stats refreshed on Tuesday: optimizer may have chosen a worse plan on Wednesday (counter-intuitively, fresh stats can change plans), (4) Check index status: SELECT status FROM dba_indexes WHERE table_name='MAIN_TABLE', (5) Use baselines: SQL Plan Baselines to lock plans for critical batch SQLs, (6) AWR Diff report: EXEC DBMS_WORKLOAD_REPOSITORY.CREATE_BASELINE(snap_id_from, snap_id_to, 'Tuesday_Baseline')."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Kubernetes cluster running banking services shows `kubectl get nodes` returns all nodes as Ready, but some pods show 'Pending' with event: 'Insufficient cpu'. The cluster has 10 nodes each with 8 CPU cores. What should be investigated?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The Kubernetes API server is overloaded and cannot schedule pods", "feedback": "Incorrect. API server overload would show different symptoms. Pod stuck Pending with 'Insufficient cpu' is a scheduling constraint."},
      {"text": "The sum of all pod CPU requests exceeds total cluster CPU capacity, OR nodes have no allocatable CPU due to system resource reservation", "feedback": "Correct. Kubernetes reserves CPU for system components. If all remaining allocatable CPU is requested by existing pods, new pods pend. Also check if nodes are tainted or have resource pressure."},
      {"text": "The pod's container image is too large to download on any node", "feedback": "Incorrect. Image pull issues show 'ImagePullBackOff', not 'Insufficient cpu'."},
      {"text": "The pods need more than 8 CPU cores each, which exceeds single node capacity", "feedback": "Incorrect. A pod requesting more CPUs than any single node can provide would also pend, but need to see the actual resource requests."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Insufficient CPU for scheduling: total requested > total allocatable. Check requests across all pods.",
    "explanation": "Diagnosis: (1) `kubectl describe nodes | grep -A 5 'Allocated resources'` — see CPU requests/limits per node, (2) `kubectl get pods --all-namespaces -o json | jq '.items[].spec.containers[].resources.requests.cpu'` — total requests, (3) Kubernetes reserves: kube-reserved + system-reserved = allocatable < total, (4) Solutions: a) Add more nodes, b) Reduce CPU requests if they're overestimated, c) Use VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscaler) for right-sizing, d) Check for zombie pods consuming resources, (5) Best practice: requests should match actual usage (right-sizing), not worst-case estimates."
  },
  {
    "question": "A monitoring team wants to reduce mean time to detect (MTTD) incidents for a banking application. Currently, MTTD is 45 minutes. What approach is MOST effective?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase the frequency of manual health checks from hourly to every 15 minutes", "feedback": "Incorrect. Manual checks are labor-intensive and still have gaps. Automated monitoring is more effective."},
      {"text": "Implement synthetic monitoring (proactive user journey simulation every 1-2 minutes) combined with real-user monitoring and correlated alerts with automatic escalation", "feedback": "Correct. Synthetic transactions running every 1-2 minutes detect issues in <2 minutes. Combined with real-user monitoring and correlated alerts, MTTD can be reduced to 2-5 minutes."},
      {"text": "Hire more on-call engineers to monitor dashboards continuously", "feedback": "Incorrect. Human monitoring of dashboards is error-prone, fatigue-affected, and expensive. Automated detection is always superior."},
      {"text": "Implement weekly report of all incidents to identify detection gaps", "feedback": "Incorrect. Weekly reports are retrospective — they improve future detection strategy, not current MTTD."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "MTTD reduction requires proactive, automated detection. Synthetic monitoring finds issues before users do.",
    "explanation": "MTTD reduction strategies: (1) Synthetic monitoring: Selenium/Playwright scripts simulating user journeys (login, transaction) every 60-120 seconds — detects functional failures, (2) Real-user monitoring (RUM): detect anomalies in actual user experience metrics, (3) Metric-based alerting: SLO-burn-rate alerts detect gradual degradation early, (4) Log anomaly detection: ML-based pattern recognition (Splunk MLTK, Elastic ML), (5) Correlation: single dashboard correlating metrics, logs, traces — reduces time to understand scope, (6) Auto-escalation: P1 alerts trigger PagerDuty/VictorOps within seconds, not after teams review dashboards."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application uses a message queue (IBM MQ) for processing transactions. Operations team observes the queue depth growing from 0 to 500,000 messages over 2 hours. The publisher rate is normal but consumer processing seems slow. What should be investigated first?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase IBM MQ queue depth limit to handle the backlog", "feedback": "Incorrect. Increasing queue limit accommodates more messages but doesn't fix why consumers can't keep up."},
      {"text": "Investigate why consumer (message processor) throughput dropped — check consumer thread count, downstream dependency (DB) response time, and consumer application errors", "feedback": "Correct. Queue growing = production > consumption. If publisher rate is normal, consumer has slowed. Common causes: DB slow, consumer thread pool exhausted, or consumer errors causing retries."},
      {"text": "Restart IBM MQ server to clear the queue backlog", "feedback": "Incorrect. Restarting MQ loses 500,000 messages unless they're persistent. Extremely disruptive."},
      {"text": "Scale down the publisher to reduce inflow temporarily", "feedback": "Incorrect. Scaling down publishers reduces business throughput. Fix the consumer issue instead."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Queue growing = producer > consumer. Publisher is normal → consumer is the problem.",
    "explanation": "Consumer investigation: (1) Check consumer application logs for errors (NullPointerException during processing = consuming but failing = message going to DLQ or retry), (2) Consumer thread count: if all threads are busy/blocked, no new messages processed, (3) DB dependency: consumer calls DB for each message — if DB is slow (10x normal), 10x fewer messages processed per hour, (4) Monitor: IBM MQ metrics — GET rate (consumption), PUT rate (production), queue depth, (5) Scale consumers horizontally if possible, (6) Check DLQ (Dead Letter Queue) depth — are messages failing processing and going to DLQ? Fix the processing error."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking production server has multiple applications running. Operations receives an alert: `df -h` shows `/` at 100%. The server is showing system slowness. What is the FASTEST way to free space without risking data loss?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Run `dd if=/dev/zero of=/bigfile` to test disk — this will show how much space is needed", "feedback": "Incorrect. This makes the problem catastrophically worse by writing zeros to fill ALL remaining disk space."},
      {"text": "Identify and delete large rotated log files that have already been archived, or truncate current log files that are actively written to using `> /path/to/logfile` (not rm)", "feedback": "Correct. Rotated compressed logs (.gz) are safe to delete if archived. For active log files being written by processes, truncate (not delete) using `> file` — deleting while process has it open doesn't release space until process closes the FD."},
      {"text": "Remove all files in /tmp to free space quickly", "feedback": "Partially valid — /tmp files are usually safe to remove but /tmp may not be the main consumer. Check what's large first."},
      {"text": "Kill all non-essential processes to stop log generation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Killing processes on a banking production server is extremely disruptive and doesn't directly free existing disk space."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Find large files first, then delete safely. Never delete files being actively written — truncate instead.",
    "explanation": "Emergency disk space recovery: (1) `du -sh /* 2>/dev/null | sort -rh | head` — find largest directories, (2) `find / -size +100M -type f 2>/dev/null | sort -k5 -rn` — files over 100MB, (3) Safe to delete: *.gz rotated logs, core dumps (/var/lib/systemd/coredump/), old package caches (/var/cache/), (4) For open-but-deleted files (lsof | grep deleted): truncate the live file: `> /var/log/app.log` (process keeps writing to truncated file), (5) Journalctl: `journalctl --vacuum-size=500M` — keep only 500MB of systemd logs, (6) CRITICAL: Never do `rm -rf` while panicking — identify before deleting."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle database configured with archivelog mode shows that the archive log destination is 95% full. Archiving has not yet stopped, but will soon. What is the CORRECT sequence of actions?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Disable archivelog mode temporarily to prevent archiving from failing", "feedback": "Incorrect. Disabling archivelog mode removes point-in-time recovery capability — catastrophic for banking production."},
      {"text": "First, move or delete old archive logs after confirming they've been backed up by RMAN, then free space, and ensure RMAN backup schedule is properly archiving and deleting", "feedback": "Correct. Archive logs can only be deleted after RMAN backup confirms they're backed up. Deleting unbackedup archive logs means those recovery points are lost."},
      {"text": "Immediately run `rm -rf` on all archive logs to free space", "feedback": "Incorrect. Deleting archive logs without confirming RMAN backup = loss of point-in-time recovery capability = catastrophic for banking."},
      {"text": "Increase archive log destination disk size by adding a new mount point", "feedback": "Correct as an additional action but not the primary solution — the underlying issue is RMAN not clearing backed-up archives."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Archive logs are for recovery. Only delete after confirmed backup. RMAN is the right tool.",
    "explanation": "Correct procedure: (1) Check RMAN backup status: LIST BACKUP OF ARCHIVELOG ALL; — identify what's been backed up, (2) If backed up: RMAN> CROSSCHECK ARCHIVELOG ALL; DELETE EXPIRED ARCHIVELOG ALL; — removes backed up archivelogs, (3) If RMAN backup is behind: run emergency RMAN backup first: RMAN> BACKUP ARCHIVELOG ALL DELETE INPUT; — backup and delete in one step, (4) Check why RMAN is not purging: DB deletion policy — RMAN> SHOW ALL; — verify RETENTION POLICY, (5) Alert monitoring: monitor archive log destination at 70% and 85% — not 95%."
  },
  {
    "question": "A production Kubernetes cluster is upgraded from v1.24 to v1.26. After the upgrade, several banking pods fail to start with 'Error: container has runAsNonRoot but image will run as root'. This error didn't appear in v1.24. What changed?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The container images were accidentally changed during the upgrade", "feedback": "Incorrect. Cluster upgrade doesn't change application images."},
      {"text": "Kubernetes v1.25 removed PodSecurityPolicy and replaced it with Pod Security Standards/Admission — stricter enforcement now flags containers running as root when runAsNonRoot is set", "feedback": "Correct. Kubernetes v1.25 removed PSP (deprecated since v1.21). The Pod Security Admission now enforces securityContext more strictly. Pods with runAsNonRoot:true will fail if the container's USER instruction runs as root."},
      {"text": "The container runtime changed from Docker to containerd in v1.26", "feedback": "Incorrect. Docker was removed in v1.24. This is not a v1.24 to v1.26 change."},
      {"text": "The namespace resource quotas were changed during cluster upgrade", "feedback": "Incorrect. Resource quotas don't affect container user enforcement."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "K8s v1.25 removed PodSecurityPolicy. The replacement enforces securityContext more strictly.",
    "explanation": "Fix: (1) Update container images to run as non-root user: add USER 1000 in Dockerfile (if images are yours), (2) For third-party images: set runAsUser: 1000 in pod spec securityContext — if image supports it, (3) If image must run as root: configure Pod Security Standards at namespace level: `kubectl label namespace banking pod-security.kubernetes.io/enforce=baseline`, (4) Baseline policy allows root with some restrictions, (5) Best practice: build all banking images to run as non-root (USER instruction in Dockerfile), (6) Migration guide: admission.k8s.io/enforce label on namespaces."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking batch processing system fails every month-end with 'ORA-01652: unable to extend temp segment by 128 in tablespace TEMP'. The batch runs month-end reports involving large sort operations on 3 years of transaction data. The TEMP tablespace is 50GB. What is the BEST long-term solution?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Create a dedicated TEMP tablespace for batch processing with 200GB capacity", "feedback": "Correct as one approach — resource isolation for batch vs OLTP temp usage. But consider query optimization as the comprehensive solution."},
      {"text": "Optimize the month-end batch queries to reduce sort operations (add appropriate indexes, rewrite sorts as hash joins, partition data), AND create a dedicated TEMP tablespace for batch", "feedback": "Correct and comprehensive. The best long-term solution addresses both the symptom (insufficient temp) and the root cause (inefficient sorting of 3 years of data)."},
      {"text": "Add 200GB of temp tablespace every month-end and remove it after", "feedback": "Incorrect. Temporary tablespace additions are permanent changes in Oracle — you can't 'remove' them easily. This is not a scalable solution."},
      {"text": "Schedule the month-end batch during low-activity hours when TEMP usage is minimal", "feedback": "Partially correct — timing helps, but doesn't fix the core issue of excessive temp usage."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Address both symptom (temp space) AND root cause (query efficiency).",
    "explanation": "Comprehensive fix: (1) Query optimization: EXPLAIN PLAN for batch SQLs — identify large sorts/hash joins, (2) Indexes: proper indexes can convert sort operations to index range scans (no sort needed), (3) Partitioning: if querying 3 years of data, partition by month — query only relevant partitions, (4) Dedicated temp: CREATE TEMPORARY TABLESPACE TEMP_BATCH TEMPFILE '/oracle/temp_batch.dbf' SIZE 100G; ALTER USER batch_user TEMPORARY TABLESPACE TEMP_BATCH — isolates batch temp from OLTP, (5) Sort_area_size: for specific batch sessions: ALTER SESSION SET sort_area_size=209715200 (200MB) — allows larger in-memory sorts."
  },
  {
    "question": "During a P1 incident bridge call, the incident manager asks: 'What is the user impact right now?' The technical team is focused on debugging logs. What should the incident manager do to get this information?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Wait for the technical team to finish log analysis before assessing user impact", "feedback": "Incorrect. User impact assessment is parallel to technical diagnosis, not sequential after it."},
      {"text": "Assign a separate person to correlate monitoring data (error rates, transaction volumes) and business metrics to quantify user impact independently of the debug investigation", "feedback": "Correct. Incident management requires parallel workstreams: (1) Technical: diagnose and fix, (2) Business impact: quantify affected users/transactions, (3) Communication: update stakeholders. These happen simultaneously."},
      {"text": "Escalate to senior management to get the user impact information", "feedback": "Incorrect. Management doesn't have real-time user impact data. Operations/monitoring teams do."},
      {"text": "Reduce the incident priority since the team doesn't know the user impact", "feedback": "Incorrect. Unknown impact doesn't mean lower priority — assume worst case until proven otherwise."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Incident management runs multiple workstreams in parallel. User impact is its own workstream.",
    "explanation": "P1 incident parallel workstreams: (1) Technical team: root cause analysis and fix, (2) Impact team: Splunk/AppDynamics/monitoring — error rate, affected users, failed transactions count, (3) Communication team: status page updates, stakeholder notifications every 15-30 minutes, (4) Customer service: brief frontline teams on workarounds for users, (5) Business impact quantification: 'X users affected, Y transactions failed, estimated loss $Z' — needed for management reporting and SLA breach calculation, (6) Timeline tracking: document all actions with timestamps for post-incident review."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Splunk Heavy Forwarder for a banking environment shows input queue is growing. Logs from the past 2 hours are not visible in the Splunk index. The HF has 4 CPU cores and the `top` shows Splunk at 95% CPU. What is most likely happening?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The Splunk indexer is down, causing logs to queue on the HF", "feedback": "Incorrect. Indexer down would cause queuing but not high CPU on HF — HF would be idle waiting for indexer connection."},
      {"text": "The Heavy Forwarder is overwhelmed processing incoming logs — possibly due to a log volume spike or expensive regex-based log parsing configured in transforms.conf", "feedback": "Correct. HF does log parsing, transformation, and forwarding. High CPU with growing queue = HF processing throughput below log input rate. Expensive transforms/props parsing can cause CPU saturation."},
      {"text": "The HF license has expired causing log processing to stop", "feedback": "Incorrect. License expiry causes indexing to stop at the indexer, not CPU saturation at the HF."},
      {"text": "The network between HF and indexer is saturated causing retransmission", "feedback": "Incorrect. Network saturation would show high network I/O, not 95% CPU on HF."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "HF at 95% CPU with growing queue = HF is the bottleneck, not indexer or network.",
    "explanation": "HF performance tuning: (1) Identify expensive transforms: Splunk btool transforms list | grep REGEX — complex regex is CPU-intensive, (2) Increase HF parallelism: parallelIngestionPipelines=2 in server.conf (up to CPU count), (3) Simplify transforms: pre-filter at the source (syslog-ng, filebeat) before HF, (4) Log volume spike: identify source flooding HF: splunkd.log — look for 'received' events per source, (5) Scale out: add more HFs behind a load balancer, (6) Monitor HF: index=_internal source=*metrics.log group=queue component=tcpout — check output queue fill levels."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application reports memory usage growing over 7 days. Heap analysis shows a `HashMap` containing `CustomerSession` objects grows indefinitely. The application handles 5,000 users/day. Sessions should expire after 30 minutes. What is the root cause?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The HashMap is too small and needs a larger initial capacity", "feedback": "Incorrect. HashMap automatically resizes. Initial capacity doesn't cause memory growth — unbounded growth does."},
      {"text": "Session expiration logic is not removing sessions from the HashMap — sessions accumulate without cleanup, causing a classic cache/map memory leak", "feedback": "Correct. If expired sessions aren't removed from the HashMap, it grows by 5,000 sessions/day × 7 days = 35,000 sessions. Over time this causes OOM."},
      {"text": "The application server needs more heap (-Xmx) to handle 5,000 daily users", "feedback": "Incorrect. Adding heap delays OOM but doesn't fix the leak — HashMap will fill any heap size eventually."},
      {"text": "JVM garbage collection is not efficient enough to remove old sessions", "feedback": "Incorrect. GC collects unreachable objects. If sessions are still in the HashMap (reachable), GC cannot collect them regardless of configuration."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Objects in a HashMap are reachable (referenced). GC cannot collect them. Application code must remove them.",
    "explanation": "Session cleanup implementation: (1) Use LinkedHashMap with removeEldestEntry() override to auto-evict oldest entries, (2) Use Caffeine/Guava Cache with expireAfterWrite(30, TimeUnit.MINUTES) — built-in TTL eviction, (3) Schedule cleanup: ScheduledExecutorService every 5 minutes removes sessions where lastAccess > 30 minutes, (4) Use WeakReference<CustomerSession> in the map — allows GC to reclaim sessions not referenced elsewhere, (5) Best practice: use battle-tested session management (HttpSession in app servers, Redis for distributed sessions) instead of custom HashMap — these have built-in expiration."
  },
  {
    "question": "A PostgreSQL replication setup has primary (Node A) and standby (Node B). During a maintenance window, Node A is rebooted. Node B does not automatically promote to primary. The team expects automatic failover. What is missing?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Node B's max_standby_streaming_delay is set too high", "feedback": "Incorrect. max_standby_streaming_delay controls query cancellation on standby, not failover behavior."},
      {"text": "PostgreSQL does not have built-in automatic failover — a separate HA tool like Patroni, repmgr, or Pacemaker is required to monitor and trigger automatic promotion", "feedback": "Correct. PostgreSQL streaming replication provides data replication but not automatic failover. HA tools (Patroni, repmgr) monitor primary health and promote standby when primary fails."},
      {"text": "recovery.conf (or primary_conninfo in PG12+) needs a failover trigger file configured", "feedback": "Partially correct — trigger file allows manual promotion, but doesn't provide automatic failover."},
      {"text": "Node B's hot_standby must be set to ON for automatic promotion", "feedback": "Incorrect. hot_standby allows read queries on standby, not automatic failover."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "PostgreSQL replication ≠ PostgreSQL HA. Separate tooling is required for automatic failover.",
    "explanation": "PostgreSQL HA options: (1) Patroni: most popular — etcd/consul for distributed consensus, automatic promotion, VIP management, REST API for health monitoring, (2) repmgr: simpler, PostgreSQL-native HA tool, automatic failover with witness node, (3) Pacemaker + Corosync: Linux HA framework, requires more configuration, (4) AWS: RDS Multi-AZ handles this automatically, (5) Manual promotion (reference): pg_ctl promote or touch /tmp/failover.trigger, update application connection strings, (6) For banking: test automatic failover regularly — validate RTO (Recovery Time Objective) against SLA."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application shows that every Monday morning at 9 AM, login response times increase from 200ms to 8-12 seconds for approximately 20 minutes. The DBA finds high 'db file sequential read' waits on the user authentication table. By 9:20 AM everything is normal. What is likely happening?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "A security attack targeting the banking portal every Monday", "feedback": "Incorrect. A security attack would show unusual access patterns, not predictable 20-minute windows."},
      {"text": "Weekend database maintenance (statistics refresh, index rebuild) causes the buffer cache to be cold Monday morning — authentication queries do physical reads until data warms up in cache", "feedback": "Correct. If weekend maintenance flushes/rebuilds indexes and statistics, or if DB is restarted Sunday night, Monday's first queries read from disk (cold buffer cache). After 20 minutes, hot data is cached and performance returns to normal."},
      {"text": "Monday is a peak day and the infrastructure is undersized", "feedback": "Incorrect. If infrastructure is undersized, the problem would persist throughout Monday, not resolve in 20 minutes."},
      {"text": "The database connection pool is not pre-warmed on Monday mornings", "feedback": "Partially relevant but pool warming happens in seconds, not causing 20-minute windows."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "20-minute performance issue every Monday morning that resolves on its own = cold cache warm-up.",
    "explanation": "Cold cache warm-up solutions: (1) Implement cache warming scripts: after weekend maintenance, run representative queries to pre-populate buffer cache before 9 AM, (2) Oracle: BEGIN DBMS_SHARED_POOL.KEEP('SELECT * FROM users WHERE 1=2'); END; — pin objects in shared pool, (3) Reschedule maintenance to Saturday night instead of Sunday night — more time for cache to warm before Monday business hours, (4) DB Cache Advisor: V$DB_CACHE_ADVICE — ensure buffer cache is large enough to hold hot authentication data permanently, (5) Application-level: warm application caches (Spring Cache, EhCache) before going live."
  },
  {
    "question": "A Kubernetes pod running a banking service shows 'Warning: Evicted' status. The node has 64GB RAM and `kubectl describe pod` shows: 'The node was low on resource: memory. Threshold quantity: 100Mi, available: 50Mi'. What caused this and how to prevent it?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The pod had a memory leak — fix the application code", "feedback": "Incorrect. While memory leaks can contribute, the eviction is a node-level memory pressure event — other pods may also be causing pressure."},
      {"text": "Kubernetes kubelet evicted the pod because the node was under memory pressure — set appropriate resource requests/limits on all pods so the scheduler can properly distribute workload", "feedback": "Correct. Kubelet evicts pods when node memory drops below eviction threshold (default 100Mi). Cause: pods without memory requests are scheduled without capacity accounting, leading to node overcommit."},
      {"text": "The pod needs a higher priority class to prevent eviction", "feedback": "Partially correct — PriorityClass affects eviction order but doesn't prevent node memory pressure. Fix root cause."},
      {"text": "Increase the node's eviction threshold to 10Mi so pods are evicted less aggressively", "feedback": "Incorrect. Reducing the threshold further risks node instability. The fix is proper resource requests."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Eviction = kubelet protecting node stability. Fix: proper resource requests so scheduler can plan.",
    "explanation": "Prevention: (1) Set memory requests AND limits on all pods: resources: { requests: { memory: '256Mi' }, limits: { memory: '512Mi' } }, (2) Without requests: scheduler doesn't know real memory needs → overcommits node, (3) Guaranteed QoS: requests = limits — pods are never evicted for resource pressure, (4) Burstable QoS: limits > requests — can be evicted, (5) BestEffort: no limits/requests — first to be evicted, (6) Use VPA (Vertical Pod Autoscaler) to right-size requests based on actual usage, (7) Check: kubectl describe node | grep -A 10 'Non-terminated Pods' for memory request totals."
  },
  {
    "question": "An Oracle database shows 'ORA-04031: unable to allocate 4096 bytes of shared memory' despite the large pool having 500MB free. The error occurs specifically during parallel query execution. What is the issue?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "The shared pool is insufficient for parallel query metadata", "feedback": "Incorrect. The question specifies large pool has free memory. Parallel query uses large pool, not shared pool."},
      {"text": "The large pool is fragmented — sufficient total free space exists but no contiguous 4KB chunk can be found due to fragmentation from previous allocations", "feedback": "Correct. ORA-04031 in large pool during parallel queries occurs when fragmentation prevents even small allocations despite apparent free space. Parallel query coordinator and slaves use large pool heavily."},
      {"text": "Parallel degree is set too high consuming all large pool chunks", "feedback": "Partially related but fragmentation is the specific cause when total free memory appears sufficient."},
      {"text": "Oracle parallel execution requires shared pool, not large pool", "feedback": "Incorrect. Parallel execution (PX) message buffers are allocated from large pool. Large pool must be configured for PX."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Space available but allocation fails = fragmentation. No contiguous chunk for even small request.",
    "explanation": "Large pool and PX: (1) Parallel execution slaves allocate PX message buffers from large pool: parallel_automatic_tuning determines allocation, (2) Fragmentation: flush large pool (may disrupt active parallel queries): EXECUTE DBMS_SHARED_POOL.PURGE(), (3) Increase large_pool_size: ALTER SYSTEM SET large_pool_size=1G, (4) Reduce PARALLEL_DEGREE or PARALLEL_MAX_SERVERS to decrease large pool demand, (5) Monitor: SELECT pool, name, bytes FROM v$sgastat WHERE pool='large pool' ORDER BY bytes DESC, (6) AMM (Automatic Memory Management): if enabled, Oracle auto-adjusts SGA components — may be competing with large pool."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking team is implementing monitoring for a new microservice. The service calls 5 downstream APIs and a database. To create the most effective alert, which metric combination best indicates real user impact?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Alert on each downstream API individually when their latency exceeds 1 second", "feedback": "Incorrect. Individual downstream alerts may fire without actual user impact (if one API is slow but the service still responds acceptably by using cache or fallback)."},
      {"text": "Alert on the composite end-to-end transaction success rate AND P99 latency from the user's perspective — only when these cross SLO thresholds", "feedback": "Correct. User-facing metrics (success rate, P99 latency from user entry point) directly measure user impact. Downstream component alerts are diagnostic tools, not primary user impact indicators."},
      {"text": "Alert on JVM heap usage and CPU utilization thresholds", "feedback": "Incorrect. Infrastructure metrics are indirect indicators. High heap doesn't necessarily mean user impact."},
      {"text": "Alert on all 5 downstream APIs plus database latency simultaneously", "feedback": "Incorrect. Alerting on all components creates alert storm and alert fatigue. User-facing SLO is the right primary alert."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Primary alert: does the user experience meet SLO? Secondary: which component is causing it?",
    "explanation": "Alert hierarchy: (1) PRIMARY (user-facing): success rate < 99.5% OR P99 latency > 2s → Page on-call, (2) SECONDARY (diagnostic): downstream API X latency > threshold → inform team, help diagnose, (3) Google SRE approach: alert on symptoms (user impact), not causes (component metrics), (4) Error budget burn: if burning SLO error budget too fast, alert — more sophisticated than fixed threshold, (5) Downstream alerts: configure as informational, not paging alerts, (6) Correlation: when primary alert fires, pre-populated dashboard shows all downstream metrics automatically — no need to page on each one."
  },
  {
    "question": "A banking application deployed in WebLogic is experiencing memory leak symptoms. A heap dump analysis shows 50,000 instances of `org.apache.xerces.parsers.SAXParser` in memory. The application creates a new SAXParser for each HTTP request. What is the correct fix?",
    "options": [
      {"text": "Increase JVM heap to accommodate 50,000 SAXParser instances", "feedback": "Incorrect. More heap delays OOM but doesn't fix the leak — instances will accumulate indefinitely."},
      {"text": "Implement SAXParser pooling or reuse — create a pool of SAXParsers shared across requests, or use ThreadLocal SAXParser per thread", "feedback": "Correct. Creating a new SAXParser per request is expensive and accumulates if not explicitly nulled. ThreadLocal or object pooling (Apache Commons Pool) efficiently reuses parsers across requests."},
      {"text": "Switch from SAX to DOM parser which doesn't have memory issues", "feedback": "Incorrect. DOM parsers can have worse memory issues (entire XML in memory). SAX is already the memory-efficient choice — the issue is parser instance accumulation."},
      {"text": "Reduce the number of HTTP requests to reduce SAXParser creation", "feedback": "Incorrect. Reducing business throughput is not a fix for a memory leak."}
    ],
    "answer": 1,
    "hint": "Object per request = object accumulation if GC can't collect them. Pool or reuse XML parsers.",
    "explanation": "SAXParser reuse: (1) ThreadLocal approach: private static final ThreadLocal<SAXParser> tlParser = ThreadLocal.withInitial(() -> factory.newSAXParser()); — one parser per thread, reused across requests, (2) SAXParserFactory is thread-safe for factory.newSAXParser(); — but SAXParser itself is not thread-safe, (3) Pool approach: Apache Commons Pool2 — GenericObjectPool<SAXParser> with max idle, max total, (4) Why accumulating: if SAXParser objects are referenced by a collection or listener that outlives the request scope, GC can't collect them, (5) Check: SAXParser implements Resetable: parser.reset() — resets state for reuse without recreation."
